SYMPTOM_TEXT: I received the second dose of the Pfizer vaccine on Friday April 9th at 6pm. I did not feel any adverse effects beyond arm soreness around the injection site until the morning of Sunday April 11th, at which point I had exacerbated joint pain (likely an inflammation response). In the evening of the 11th, I noticed the soft tissues of both my mouth and vulva felt more raw/sensitive than usual. On the 12th this feeling persisted, with canker sores/mouth ulcers forming in my mouth/throat and a continued stinging/irritated feeling in my vulva. On the 13th this manifested as vulval ulcers, which were painful on their own and with pain dramatically increased while urinating. During the night of the 13th/morning of 14th I also woke up several times feeling either chilly/clammy or overheated, and took 800mg ibuprofen and slept through to the morning of the 14th. By the time I woke up I no longer had chills/fever symptom, but mouth and vulval ulcers had both progressed. The appearance of the vulval ulcers was crater-like patches with a white coloration surrounded by raised red rims, with several touching/against each other and surrounding tissue also inflamed/sensitive. On the 15th I made an appointment with urgent care as I was unable to use the bathroom without extreme pain and was unable to wipe the area and had to rinse in the shower to stay clean instead. From the Urgent Care clinician I was prescribed a 5% topical lidocaine ointment, a 4% over the counter lidocaine alternative option, and an antiviral course of Acyclovir. Bloodwork was done to rule out STIs. Applying the ointment 4-5 times a day before using the bathroom was the most effective part of treatment, although constant discomfort and inability to wear tight clothing/wash the area normally persisted for the following week. At peak, there were 10 visible ulcers ranging from 0.3cm-0.8cm in diameter, located on both inside sides of the labia and with some presenting as "kissing sores". After April 20th, they slowly grew smaller and began to recede although intense pain persisted. At this point my mouth sores had also diminished and were fading at a faster rate than the vulvar sores, with minimal disruption to function besides avoiding particularly sharp/spicy/salty foods. I kept up use of the topical numbing cream on the vulvar ulcers until April 26th, at which point most sores had healed and I was able to urinate and bathe in a normal manor, although I still needed to be gentle/the area still felt sensitive. At the time of writing this report (April 28th), I still see some redness/potential scarring but there are no longer open sores and there is no noticeable pain/sensitivity.
LAB_DATA: Blood test on Friday April 16th to rule out STIs; results were negative including for HSV
OTHER_MEDS: Jasmiel (birth control), Dapsone 5% (topical facial acne ointment), Clindamycin Phosphate 1.2% and Benxol Peroxide 2.5% gel (topical facial acne ointment)
HISTORY: I do not have a diagnosis as my doctors have not been able to determine a direct cause, but I am more prone to developing canker sores/mouth ulcers than average, and I have had canker sore outbreaks triggered by bad colds/upper respiratory infections in the past.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Ran a fever (100 - 101) at home for day and a half. Took ibuprofen and acetaminophen intermittently as fever spiked over and over. Woke around 2:40 am on Saturday morning feeling nauseous and lightheaded. Then lost consciousness for several seconds up to a minute. Daughter called 911. Paramedics came and took me to ER where fluids were given intravenously along with morphine. White blood cell count was double (20). ER doctor thought symptoms were due to bacterial meningitis. Tried to perform spinal tap but unsuccessful. Said I was septic. Sent to downtown hospital for radiology to perform spinal tap. Once transferred, my fever was 102.3 and I was shaking with chills. Infectious Disease doctor thought maybe I didn?t have meningitis but wanted to wait and see how I progressed over the next several days. Rash developed on back. Fever subsided after two days in hospital. Severe headaches continued for several days.
LAB_DATA: CAT scan performed to rule out heart and neurological problems. Blood taken to be sent to lab to check for bacteria growth. Urine sample also sent to lab to check for issues. No bacterial growth shown in either. Spinal tap performed unsuccessfully to check for meningitis.
OTHER_MEDS: Armour Thyroid, Flovent, Ritual Daily Vitamins
PRIOR_VAX: Low grade fever, fatigue

I don't want to get her in trouble, but I wanted to report it in case this pain continues.

Patient did not receive any medication during event and syncope resolved spontaneously.

My menstrual cycle changed drastically, temporarily, right around my vaccines. I am extremely regular with a normal cycle length of 26 or 27 days. I had my hormones checked less than a year prior to the vaccines as part of a routine exam and was told not to expect any age-related changes anytime soon. The cycle I was in when I received my first dose (12/30/20) was extended by about 3 days - not groundbreaking, but noticeable to me. Then following my second dose (1/27/21), I completely missed a period. So the 2 cycles during which I had my vaccines were 30 days and 53 days long instead of my usual 26-27. Now, a couple months later, I have returned to my usual schedule.  It was unsettling for my cycle to be affected and at first it didn't occur to me that it could have been related to the vaccine, but the timing was exactly aligned so it seems very likely it was causal.

The day after the 2nd vaccine, there was widespread rash over trunk of body - front and back.  This started about one week after the first vaccine, with a few areas on the abdomen; I did not connect this with the vaccine, until after the 2nd dose.  The areas started as round, crusty areas (almost like a ringworm look); no blisters or oozing.  within the week after the 2nd dose, my full torso was covered in this rash.  It was not itchy, unless I got overheated or sweaty;  my entire skin became severely dry and flaky.  The rash spread beyond the trunk to the arms and upper legs.  I received a steroid injection, after several weeks.  There was a biopsy done of one area; it returned as being  guttate psoriasis.  I have NEVER had any rash this severe.  I did not fit the causes of this diagnosis (strep throat for most); I did not even have a slight sore throat, and I certainly am not in the adolescent or young adult category. I have mostly recovered, but not fully.  I also developed pronounced vertical double vision.  With regular hydrating eye drops, this is being corrected.
LAB_DATA: There was a biopsy done of one area on 2/23/21; it returned as being  guttate psoriasis. I did not fit the usual criteria for developing this. There was an eye exam done on 4/5/21; the Ophthalmologist believed the cause of the double vision to be related to extreme dry eyes.

Arm pain, arm swelling, bruising at the site of the injection, loss of grip strength in injection arm, all within 10 minutes of vaccination. Within a few hours, tiredness set in, additional loss of grip strength in both hands, but especially in the arm that received the vaccination. 9 hours after the shot, severe fatigue set in, as well as hot and cold flashes, switching between fever and chills, headache, excessive sweating, weakness, nausea, vomiting, joint pain, body aches, skin pain, and flare-ups of old injuries. I woke with tremendous, debilitating neck pain as well, which was the site of previous whiplash injuries, in both my neck and lower back, and my knees hurt as well. Woke every hour or so throughout the night, severe symptoms. By the next morning after the shot, the fever and chills had stopped, as well as the nausea and vomiting. Fatigue remained, headache on and off, and body aches. By day 3 most symptoms had gone away except for tiredness. By day 4 I started to notice sun sensitivity, and on day 6 have developed what seems to be a heat rash? My forearms are hot, red, sensitive, and reactive as well. Every day since the shot I have gotten tired in the afternoon as well, even if earlier in the day I felt OK. Have had mild shortness of breath in addition, but nothing that has stopped me from regular activity. As a 25 year old, I experienced incredibly severe symptoms, and this was my first shot of Moderna. No known previous exposure to Covid, either. Noticed that symptoms started worsening rapidly around 6 p.m. the day of my shot after taking my borth control pill as well. Wondering if related, or possibly coincidence.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient received 2nd dose of COVID-19 vaccine in vaccine clinic (Pfizer). Patient reports a history of light-headedness/dizziness with medical procedures involving needles. Approximately 5 minutes after injection, patient reported feeling dizzy. She was alert and oriented x3, denied any difficulty breathing or swallowing, no rash or itching, pupils equal and reactive, visual tracking WNL. I elevated her legs and advised her to remain in our observation area for 30 minutes. At 1:46pm, I was advised by vaccinator that patient remained dizzy. This was approx ~20 minutes after vaccination. Patient remained stable, alert and oriented. At 2:01pm I was called by Dr  and advised to come evaluate patient (I was eating my lunch at the time). Patient remained with feet elevated, alert and oriented x3 with equal and reactive pupils. HR 72 BP 138/78. Patient drank some apple juice, No SOB, rash.  I went to urgent care to see if it would be possible for patient to come lay down on a stretcher there to help with dizziness. Urgent care requested that I call rapid response and 911. I advised UC that this was not a medical emergency and the patient is stable, we just don't have any area for her to lay down. Ultimately, I left UC and advised patient that they would not take her unless we call rapid response. Patient declined. I put a blanket on the floor for her and helped her to lay down on the floor. After about 10 minutes of laying on the floor, she was able to get up and go to the restroom. She walked back to the observation area and sat in chair while husband brought car around. Patient ambulated to car without difficulty or help approx 1 hour after vaccine was administered.

She got her vaccine, she was feeling fine, the person noticed that she was in hiking gear and her dog as she had just had a 5 mile hike.  He had a drawing feeling in her left arm, which she ignored and otherwise felt fine.  Got the dog in the car, started to drive home, and got on her exit and within 3-5 minutes to get on the road going to her street felt a little weird and had blurry vision, and then it was really blurry and then she realized she was having a reaction.  There was dirt on the right side of the road and turned her car there and remember hitting the hazard lights and not having any vision at all.  Her left side was completely numb, and her right arm was extremely heavy and she was able to get her phone, but could move her fingers still and kept clicking on her phone until she got the Town Center where she got the vaccine.  She got a hold of them and got a hold of someone, and then she was completely paralyzed with a swollen tongue as well, and not able to be understood.  She stayed with her on the phone and was hardly able to make out the signs to let them know where possibly was so that they could find her.  She could barely feel her fingers at that point, and was just able to move her eyes.  She also felt fuzzy and was able to communicate.  The lady got hold of 9-1-1 and able to look up her phone # from the vaccine center who had her address and information.  It was a 3 way phone call, and it took them 35-45 minutes to find her, and two police officers passed by her right next to her with hazzards on.   Finally she heard the fire truck and was able to tell the lady that the ambulance went by her and they finally found her.   Her pulse was irratic and was able to tell them that she was not able to move and that her chest was heavy and took her to the ambulance.  She was able to move her arm a little bit and then it fell back down again.  Her vital signs were not normal so they were going to take her to the hospital.  They texted her exboyfriend to come and get her dog and he came and got her car and dog.   They took her to the hospital and they were not able to get vein access on the ambulance, and they put her in a wheelchair and not able to hold her head up.     She was in the wheelchair for about 4 1/2 hours without any vein access, no blood drawn and nobody attending to her.  Finally a nurse came in and put her in another wheelchair and pushed her to the other side and was able to get a little more comfortable.   The nurse came in and said something about her Ex-boyfriend who is a heart surgeon at that particular hospital.  Once she was on this new wheelchair and was finally able to move her toes, hands, and fingers and little by little sensation came back as she was a gymnast for 30 years and was flexing to try to gain motion.   She was able to finally get up and weakly walk and they released her after giving her a  Benadryl.     Since going home she feels heavy (arms feels like cement), weaker, and does not feel completely herself, and went for a walk yesterday (which she is normally able to hike 5-8 miles) and has been dropping things due to either weakness or nerve issues.  It has taken a toll on her and it?s hard for her to take her dogs up and down the stairs without extreme fatigue.   Loss of appetite and loss of strength.   She is a writer and is going to publish a paper regarding this as she feels she was not given the right information and proper treatment at the hospital.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I had the shot sometime between 1:20 and 1:30 pm. After about 15 minutes slight tickle in throat and a little cough. I left the test site at 30 minutes. Since I have Sjogren's I always have a dry throat and mouth, so I attributed the tickle/cough to that. Then I went back to my office and ate lunch. Over the next half hour I started feeling tight in the chest (like if I've been around an aerosol that I'm sensitive to) and the coughing continued. I also had some wheezing. I sucked on Luden's lozenges for the last 90 minutes I was at work and drank some hot tea. When I got home, I used my Albuterol inhaler and took a Benadryl and laid down. This took care of the wheezing and I felt better. The next day (4/16), I coughed all day long at work and had to clear my throat a lot.  Drank a lot of hot tea and used some cough drops. On 4/17, I felt like my sinus infection from a month prior was coming back. I took some cold/sinus stuff to get through the day, but by that night, I had a fever and just felt unwell. I made an appointment to see my doctor on 4/19 to talk to her about the reaction to the shot, but prior to the appointment, I went and got tested  and was found out I was positive for COVID. I then called my doctor's office back and was told to just stay home and let them know if my symptoms got worse and my appointment was cancelled. The caseworker assigned to me by the state ascertained that he felt my first day of Covid was 4/17 and that everything prior was a reaction to the Moderna shot. I then stayed home through 4/27 and am back at work today.
CUR_ILL: sinus infection (not diagnosed by a professional) about a month prior to the vaccination.
PRIOR_VAX: fever and body aches after 2020 flu shot
ALLERGIES: Sulfa, latex Banannas. Sensitivity to mangos, some tree nuts and peanuts depending on quantity ingested.  Cats, rabbits, ferrets, bird dander, various pollens. Some aerosol sprays.

Mother agreed to the second dose which is scheduled. 2 others that week were found to have been under 18. It was the 2nd/3rd week Ct opened vaccination to anyone over 16. This age of course was intended for Pfizer only. We don't provide Pfizer. Subsequently signs were placed indicating min age of 18,staff were reinforced to check age and a age calculation based on birthday and date of clinic was completed and included as a column in the daily list of scheduled clinic appointments distributed to front desk personel, vaccinators and vaccinator assistants for review at contact. There were no outcome adverse events associated with this vaccination.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The day of my second injection, I had soreness in my injection site. The following day, about 32 hours later, I felt warm, took my temperature, it was 99.9. I also had begun to have mid back pain that came on and intensified quickly. I had done nothing to cause an injury to my back prior to the pain starting. Over the next 1 1/2 days my pain traveled to my low back, the site of my lumbar fusion. The pain was extremely intense, reaching a 9-10 level. My sciatic nerve was effected and I had weakness in my right leg. I saw my family doctor the next morning. She prescribed pain medication and prednisone for 5 days.  My symptoms began to alleviate within another day, but I am still having some residual effects. If the pain does not subside I will contact my surgeon for further investigation. The timing of my symptoms, and the lack of any activity that could?ve caused injury, seems too coincidental not to be a side effect of the vaccine.
LAB_DATA: None at this time.  I plan on having x-rays soon.

Patient came to vaccination site for the Janssen Covid-19 vaccine on April 09, 2021. After receiving the vaccine, given by a Medical Assistant, he stated that he was ?not feeling himself and was lightheaded?. Medical Assistant, told him to put his car seat back and that she was going to get the automatic BP cuff to take his BP. Medical assistant also let two RNs, know about the incident and they also observed the patient when he was getting his BP taken by Medical Assistant at 9:10am. The first BP was taken on the left arm and was 199/119 and pulse was 72. The second was taken immediately after on the right arm by a RN and was 191/116 and pulse was 78. At 9:22am, RN called our Pharmacist and explained the symptoms the patient was having. She advised the nurses to call EMS. The RNs then took BP again at 9:23 am on the left arm, this time it was 199/116 and pulse was 72. The RNs explained to the patient they were going to have to call EMS to take him to the hospital due to his hypertension. Patient refused EMS transport and stated he would go to his doctor, but that he wants a manual BP taken. The RNs stated he would need to call someone to pick him up to transport him to his doctor. Patient called wife to pick him up. RN stated at 9:27am that a staff member was going to get the manual BP cuff. At 9:35am second RN checked patient and he stated he ?felt fine?. At 9:45am, second RN checked patient again, and he stated he was ?feeling better?. At 9:55am, second RN checked BP with the manual BP cuff on the left arm and it was 215/118 and pulse 75. At 10:00 am second RN gave patient a bottle of water, because he stated he was thirsty. Second RN asked to check BP again at 10:01am on the left arm, manually and it was 194/115 and pulse was 81. Second RN took manual BP again at 10:06 am and it was 190/110 and pulse was 82. Crackers were also given to patient at this time. At 10:18am wife picked up patient and took him to his MD office at 10:18.  On April 10th, 2021, at 10:27am, RN reached out to patient via phone but patient did not pick up or call back.
LAB_DATA: Patient was taken to PCP. We were unable to get in contact with him about tests post vaccination.

At the direction of my primary care doctor, I went to an urgent care where my blood pressure was around 140/80 (I do not have a personal history of high blood pressure, and it was just checked at a normal rate at few weeks prior to receiving the vaccine) and my resting heartrate sat in the high 140s. The urgent care I went to at the time did not have a working EKG; however, they monitored my vitals and provided Motrin for the pain. After about an hour at urgent care, my resting heartrate lowered to 130s and the pain subsided. By the next morning, it still hovered around 110 and my blood pressure remained slightly elevated; however, the chest pains and pressure had completely subsided. The timeline for pain lasted roughly 5 hours, the timeline for heightened resting heart rate and blood pressure lingered for about 12 hours.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient hospitalized from 4/18/21-4/23/21  4/18 Hospital Day 1: Patient (pt) presented to the ER via EMS for aphasia/altered mental status that began that AM. Pt had received his 2nd COVID19 vaccine (Moderna) x3 days prior. Pt had generalized body aches/fever and was taking acetaminophen for his symptoms with mild relief per wife. Per ER notes, patient had clear speech but was not making sense and easily agitated.   4/19-4/21 Hospital Day 2-4: Patient with altered mental status. Was non-verbal and easily agitated. There was concern for encephalitis, infectious vs autoimmune. On 4/19, antibiotics were discontinued and patient was being treated with steroids for possible autoimmune encephalitis.  4/22 Hospital Day 5: Patient was doing better and more talkative. Patient was able to have a limited conversation, appeared alert and oriented with some slow speech. Per medical chart, family reported patient was at "50% back to baseline."   4/23 Hospital Day 6: Patient was back at baseline and completed 3 days of IV steroids. Patient reported not being able to recall anything from "Saturday 4/17 to Wednesday 4/21". Patient was discharged on 4/23 and recommended to follow up with neurology and was not discharged with any steroids.   Treatments:  Fever: APAP 1 IVPB x1 (4/18-4/19), APAP 650 mg PO x1 (4/20-4/21) Encephalitis: Methylprednisolone 125 mg IVPB x1 (4/18); Methylprednisolone 500 mg IVPB BID (4/19-4/23) ID: Acyclovir 700 mg IVPB q8h (HSV infection) [4/18-4/19]; Cefepime 2 g IVPB x1 (Sepsis) [4/18]; Ceftriaxone 2 g IVPB q12h (CNS infection) [4/18-4/19]; Vancomycin 2.25 g IVPB x1, 1.5 g IVPB q12h (CNS infection) [4/18-4/19]

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient reports receiving 2 Pfizer COVID vaccines. The first one was on 3/17/21 with lot # EN6207 with no adverse reactions. She received her second one on 4/5/21 with lot #EP7533. She reports she started "feeling bad" 4/6/21-4/11/21. She noticed left sided neck swelling on 4/11/21. She went to urgent care and was seen by an NP and was told to go to for a CT scan the next day since it was on a Sunday.  Patient reports she went home and had further left sided neck swelling and difficulty breathing. She "couldn't catch her breath". EMS was called and she was transported per her request to Hospital. She had a 9 day hospital stay and was told she was having a severe reaction to the vaccine and that she had pneumonia with fluid in her lungs and fluid around her heart. She was treated with 2 antibiotics, IV fluids, and a diuretic. Patient had a follow up with her primary care on Monday 4/26/21 with NP and was told her heart and lungs sounded clear. She has a follow up appt scheduled with her lung doctor Dr on 5/24/21. Patient did not say why she has seen a lung doctor before but that she had been seeing this doctor prior to this adverse reaction. She was told in the hospital that it was not normal to be having this much swelling. Patient states she still feels weak and is still somewhat short of breath.
LAB_DATA: CT scan, blood work, IV fluids,  2 antibiotics, and diuretic.

My father experienced an acute stroke,  1month +7days after receiving his 2nd shot. We are reporting this because when we mentioned the stroke to members of our church, there were at least 2 others who knew of someone in my fathers age group who also had a stroke 1 month after their 2nd covid vaccine shot. My father is currently at hospital, and is being moved to Rehab Center today. (April 28, 2021)     On Saturday, April 24th, he woke up with wobbly legs around 3am, accompanied with an odd sensation in one of his arms, and legs. He went on about his day, but felt off. He fell around 2:20pm, I was called by mom. My husband and I arrived about 10 minutes later. He was up, and walking at that point, but his speech was very slurred. We checked his blood levels (159), and went through the stroke symptoms, and drove him to Hospital, where they immediately took him in under stroke protocols. It was determined he had an acute stroke.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: patient said "I'm supposed to tell you that I might pass out after a shot." I asked him some questions about when this typically occurs. He states that he has about 30 seconds to know if he is going to pass out. His wife who was right beside the patient said he also he skin turns color as well. I gave him his vaccination. I had him sit in chair to see how he was feeling. He said he was feeling fine. I had him sit about five feet from me in supportive, armed chair. I was preparing to vaccinate his wife. We looked over and his face started turning pale and green. His wife and I immediately went to both his sides to support him and lower his head to his lap. He became conscious about 5-10 seconds later. This all occurred within 3 minutes of the administration of the shot. I gave him a drink. I continued to observe him for 15 minutes until he left. He was alert and fine when leaving the store. I called the patient's home on April 25, 2021. Patient was at work. I spoke with his wife who said he was feeling fine. I recommended he check in with his doctor regarding second shot.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Seven days after receiving vaccination I broke out in a rash that increased in severity for three days. It was located around my waist, down my legs and ankles. It started as raised red bumps that itched. By day four the clusters formed a flat mass of red- like blood pooling under my skin. The rash started Saturday night and I consulted with my healthcare provider in. I was in Denver for the week and she encouraged me to be evaluated. On Tuesday April 13 I saw Urgent Care.  He seemed stumped - especially since the onset of rash was seven days after injection. He put me on a six day course of methylprednisolone.  I began the course that day and that stopped the itching  and the daily multiplication of spots and spreading blood like areas.  Today, April 28 I am home in Portland and the spots are fading.  Both health care providers went through list of common irritants and they did not apply. I was traveling with my husband who did not develop any rashes or spots.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 1 minute after administration of vaccine, patient lost consciousness and fell from chair striking the right side of head on pavement. He was rolled from prone, assessed and had a pulse but initially was not breathing. 911 called Within 10 second, had spontaneous return of respirations, consciousness and was oriented to person, place, time. Sustained an abrasion to his head, complaints of mild HA, no neck pain or signs of cervical injury or other trauma. Vitals monitored. Given fluids, juice. Assessed by paramedics and refused transport to ED for further evaluation. Given ice and called a friend for a ride home. Observed for nearly 1 hour after LOC and had returned to baseline mentation. Advised to call 911 or go to ED if worsening of HA, vision changes, confusion, falls, nausea, vomiting due to concerns for head trauma. Assessment is that this was likely a vasovagal episode and patient reported similar experience with immunization in past, in retrospect. Discussed that this is not a contraindication for 2nd dose but that he should be sure he is well hydrated and advise healthcare providers of history of vasovagal with first dose. The county will work with him to schedule 2nd dose at a health clinic attended by EMS (on site).
PRIOR_VAX: after the event, he reported 'passing out' with previous vaccination. Could not remember when or which vaccine.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 4/7/21 around 630pm began to feel ill and had sore arm. By about 1030pm, had significant body aches, headache, clammy skin, vomiting, diarrhea, near passing out, fast heart beat, with fever. These symptoms lasted about 48 hours. The next 48 hours just had ill feeling with extreme fatigue. Come 4/12/21, I had nausea, headache, fever of about 100.4 and body aches. By 4/14/21, I ended up going to the ER for shortness of breath, chest tightness, extreme fatigue and voice hoarseness. Those doctors performed several labs to include Chest CT which showed elevated D-Dimer levels. An EKG was performed which was baseline. Ultrasound of my veins was performed. They also did a COVID test which was negative. They sent me home and told me to rest and drink lots of fluid. On 4/16/21, I had a video call with my doctor who didn't like the sound of my voice and straining to catch my breath and I was sent to urgent care/ER. They admitted me as an ER visit due to my continued shortness of breath, cough, sore throat, night sweats, dizziness, chest tightness along with my voice being hoarse. Another COVID test was performed and was negative. During their exam, my oxygen levels were dropping into the low 80s and my heart rate was in the 120s and 130s. Their CT scan was down so they sent me to another ER where another CT scan was performed. Another COVID test was performed and was negative.  My D-Dimer was elevated, liver enzymes was slightly elevated and again my oxygen levels were lower than would like to see and elevated heart rate. I ended up being admitted into the hospital for an overnight stay to monitor my symptoms. They treated me for suspected blood clot, shortness of breath, chest tightness. I was given 2 shots of heparin in the stomach, IV fluids, multiple vitamins in attempt to boost my immune system, along with ADVAIR and Albuteral. My discharge diagnose from the hosptial was Acute Bronchitis, Anxiety disorder, Recent Moderna 2nd dose COVID vaccine with significant side effects in the form of fever, generalized weakness and dizziness.

Wednesday (today) all the symptoms from Tuesday are still present with the added symptom that maintaining proper posture through my left shoulder is also painful so now I'm hunching on my left side.

I felt mild symptoms the day after the vaccine (sore arm, headache, slight fever).  Otherwise I felt fine.  When I got my period three weeks after the vaccine, it was by far the worst period I've had in years.  I have had terrible cramps for four days (even though I stopped bleeding on the third day).  I couldn't stand up straight for two days because the cramps were so bad and I had to stay in bed most of the time.  My period was heavier than normal with really big clots.  My digestion has been really impacted during this time, too.  Usually during my period, my digestion is very fast and my bowels clean out, but I've been super constipated this time.  I also am having hot flashes.  The cramps are terrible.  None of the remedies I typically use for menstrual cramps are doing anything.  I track my cycle and am very aware of my body and what my periods are like and this has been absolutely unlike anything before.  I haven't had a period this bad since I was a teenager.  It actually felt a lot like my period was in reverse. CUR_ILL: My mom suffered advanced Alzheimer's disease. She was very healthy otherwise. With no other medical histories.  She was in the hospital for a PEG procedure and was getting transferred to the nursing home for rehab. They gave her the J & J COVID vaccine shot right before she left the hospital where she was tested negative for COVID that morning. My mom went into cardiac arrest about an hour after the shot in the ambulance en route to the nursing home. They were able to revive her at the arrival hospital (near the nursing home); however, with severe brain damage that she remained unresponsive.  Upon arrival at the second hospital, they tested her again for COVID and this time it was positive. My mom passed away the following day and her death certificate says the cause of death is COVID. This is SOOOOOO misleading and I actually feel it's outright wrong. She didn't die from the COVID just because she tested positive. She could be very well be tested positive for other bacteria or virus, but she didn't die from them. The J & J vaccine needs to be reexamined. How many of such cases like my mom's are out there? We are not following science here at all!
ALLERGIES: Usually sensitive to medications of all kind. Usually need smaller dosage; otherwise, she would get increased heartbeat and/or heavy breathing

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Within 12 hours of vaccine, I experienced fever, chills and sweats. I awoke from my sleep at this point, which was 4AM Friday morning. During the day on Friday, I experienced major fatigue and lethargy and had no emotional symptoms, save for being slightly annoyed/irritated about my condition. I began menstruation on Friday, April 9. Further, I slept 4pm-8pm, did some computer work from 9pm-3am, and went back to sleep. These symptoms were expected. Saturday's symptoms were not expected, regardless of onset of menstruation, and are what I would consider the adverse event. All day Saturday, I experienced massive melancholy, sadness, hopelessness, and general emotional angst. This is not normal for me, even during my period; I experienced this affect consistently years ago, from 2015-2017, when I was originally diagnosed with depression. Since 2017/2018, I have been in a much healthier emotional state, and have used an SSRI for the last 6 months with success. The following day, Sunday, I began a monophasic combination birth control, which was an original plan prescribed by a physician.  Following this, I experienced roughly 7-10 days of adverse emotional response, namely anger and aggression and mood swings, until I stopped using the new birth control on April 22. My emotional wellbeing took this roughly 7-10 days to recover. The mood change I experienced on Saturday, April 10, based on my previous experiences, was more similar to the mood change I experienced while being depressed rather than the mood change I experience from menstruation and PMS. I strongly request thoughtful consideration of the impact of the vaccine on short-term emotional and mental health changes. I was able to recover from it, and I believe that was because of my experience dealing with depression and mood swings in years past.
HISTORY: Depression, controlled at time of Vaccination

Patient got his 1st dose of the Pfizer COVID-19 vaccine (Lot #: EW0179, Exp: 5/1/21) at 1444 on 04/27/21 and at about 1446 started feeling dizzy like he was going to faint. This client understood what was going on and while sitting in the vaccination chair, he slowly put his hands on the floor and put himself in the seated position. He then slowly laid down on the floor and put his legs up on his chair preparing for this syncopal episode. The EMT was alerted by this client's nurse that he felt dizzy and then notified the lead nurse, about the situation. The client was lying down on the floor for a couple minutes and at about 1448 was able to get up and sit himself back on the chair. Client felt stable enough to walk over to the observation area and sit down in the zero gravity chair for a few minutes. The client drank some water while sitting in the zero gravity chair and at about 1452 was no longer dizzy or light headed and went over to sit in one of the regular chairs in the observation area to wait out the rest of his 15 minute period. The client explained that syncopal episodes after vaccinations regularly happen to him and that this is not out of the ordinary. The client explained that he ate and drank before his vaccination, takes no medications, and has no medical history. At about 1500 the client was stable and was able to ambulate out of the facility and to his car and verbalized feeling capable of driving himself home since he was no longer feeling dizzy or lightheaded.
PRIOR_VAX: Syncopal episode to flu immunization for the past few years. (other information unknown).

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Within 15-minutes of vaccination, the patient reported rapid palpitations. EMS evaluated the patient on-site. The patient was hypotensive (107/67) with a successful, unchanged vagal maneuver test. EKG demonstrated paroxysmal supraventricular tachycardia. EMS administered 0.5L IV normal saline and transported the patient to hospital Emergency Department. In the ED, EMS stated that the patient still had palpitations, but that their initial tachycardia (170bpm) had slightly improved (130bpm) after IV fluid. Physician administered an additional 1L normal saline. Second EKG did demonstrate SVT and physician was planning to administer Adenosine, but the patient's heart rate spontaneously improved. Upon re-evaluation, the patient remained in NSR and asymptomatic with an unremarkable work-up. After a negative D-Dimer, the physician ruled out a PE. The patient was discharged with diagnoses of SVT and palpitations with instructions to follow-up with a cardiologist.
LAB_DATA: EKG#1 (4/19): NSR, tachycardic rate 134bpm, no acute ischemic changes, no STEMI, not SVT clear p waves noted  EKG#2 (4/19): SVT nonspecific T-wave flattening, rate 141 bpm, no STEMI  EKG#3 (4/19): NSR, rate 81 bpm, no acute ischemic changes, no STEMI  CBC/CMP (4/19): Unremarkable  D-Dimer (4/19): Negative  Troponin (4/19): <0.02  CXR (4/19): No radiographic evidence of acute cardiopulmonary disease.

Patient received COVID19 Pfizer BioNTech vaccination approximately 2:20p. After vaccination administering provider requested patient wait for 15 minutes prior to leaving. Approximately 2:22p patient began to feel faint - lightheadness, clammy skin, sweating and pale skin. Patient fainted at 2:24p. Patient remained in her chair and did not slump nor fall out of the chair. Two pharmacists were with the patient to assist the patient to the floor if needed, however was not necessary. The patient regained responsiveness within a couple of minutes. When regaining consciousness the patient was alert and oriented. She was provided a water and cold coke. Upon questioning the patient revealed the only thing she had eaten for the day was a muffin at noon. The patient stated feeling weak and hot. The patient was offered a snack, however declined. After drinking some of the coke the patient began to feel better. Patient was not diabetic. At 2:37p the patient's blood pressure was 114/81 and had a pulse of 95. The patient remained in her chair with supervision while coordinating a ride from her husband. Per the patient request she was transported to the front of the store at 2:50p via wheelchair to wait for her ride. She was picked up by her husband at 3:00p and was able to get out of the wheel chair and into the vehicle under her own power. The patient was instructed to continue to rest, hydrate, and eat something upon arriving home The husband was informed of the situation and informed if her condition worsened to call emergency services for additional help.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: severe nausea, fever at the highest at 40.9 C (~105F) for about 3 hours followed by chills/fever over night ~38C, head and joint aches. All nearly resolved now (3 pm 04/28) I am reporting this to add to statistics and help vaccine development. I am allowing this report to be shared with the vaccine manufacturer besides governmental health officials.

Normal reaction the following day, strong fatigue, headache, nausea, arm soreness. Disappeared 36 hours later. 3 days later experienced heavy nausea, anxiety, gastrointestinal discomfort. Heavy bloating, inability to pass gas, loose stool/diarrhea all week. 7 days post vaccination symptoms came back, feeling of wanting to vomit, strong nausea, loss of appetite. 7-14 days later lost majority of appetite, eating aversion, heavy bloating, nausea and continuing diarrhea. Weakness, fatigue and shaking. Received Stool sample and blood test April 13. Elevated levels of albumin and red blood cell count. Doctor said it was most likely from dehydration. Zofran prescribed April 13 and only taken 2 days. Nausea subsided and ability to eat came back slowly. Since April 15th have been eating more food, but still have to force myself to eat. Hunger pangs rarely felt, only know when hungry when stomach churns and fatigue sets in. Today, April 28, still experiencing slight anxiety, loose stools once every other day, brain fog and depression. Lack of emotion, irritability and  periodic upset stomach still persist, along with appetite loss. Am able to eat filling meals again, but no appetite makes food less appealing. Failure to thrive still evident and feeling like I won't get better evident. Treatment during illness was minimal, urgent care did nothing other than prescribe zofran. Gastroenterologist and GP cannot see me for another 2 weeks.
LAB_DATA: Stool test, Blood Test April 13. Tested positive for blood in stool, elevated albumin levels, elevated RBC, hemoglobin and hemocrit, but only slightly.

Approximately 10 minutes after recieving the vaccine, the patient honked her horn to call a staff member over. RN approached vehicle and the patient stated she didn't feel well. Patient appeared pale. RN sent another staff member to get water, at which time the patient stopped responding to questions. The patient remained in her car, with the seat belt on - her eyes rolled into the back of her head and she began having jerky movements. 911 was called. HR was feint and BP was not able to be felt (too low, even with manual cuff). The patient came to, after about 45 seconds. RN asked the patient her children's names and the patient talked gibberish. About 1 minute later the patient began speaking in clear sentences. 0.5mL of epinephrine were administered. Blood glucose was 123. At 1:50 we were able to get a HR of 80 and a BP of 128/100. Oxygen was 100% with 2L via nasal canula. Patient was transported to Hospital.

Symptoms lasted for roughly 45 minutes.  Suspected CVA.  MRI done in hospital was found to be consistent with microinfarcts in the left hemisphere of the brain, mostly along the cortical ribbon with a single lesion in the left parasagittal/lateral pons.  Full neuro and cardio workup is currently being done. ECHO w/ bubble study was weakly positive and plans are for TEE today.  Otherwise, no exact cause identified and few risk factors. Found out that the patent was taking no medications prior and had no past medical history and was otherwise a 34 YO healthy male, who received their first dose of Moderna COVID-19 vaccine on 4/22.  3 days later the patient had this event.  The timing of everything makes me report this as the potential is there that this is a  vaccine ADE and plausible reason for this thrombotic event.
OTHER_MEDS: Patient has no PMH and on no medications at home according to EMR

After 10 min, patient's wife screams that her husband is not feeling well. Pharmacist rushes to the patient and sees his body shaking in the seat and asks a customer to lay him on the ground. After my second dose of Moderna, at about 7:00 pm I noticed that my glands in my neck were hurting, almost like a sore throat. At 9:00 I went to bed because I was extremely tired and I just shook. At first I was not cold, however after about an hour of shaking I became cold along with the shaking and just could not warm up. My head hurt and it felt like someone took a zip tie and put it around my chest.  My breathing was not normal, but rather shallow. I took my temperature around midnight and it was 101.5 degrees. I took Tylenol and tried to sleep. About 4 am I started sweating and then getting cold. This went back and forth for hours. Every 4 hours I got up and took more Tylenol. My chest and head continued to hurt and I stayed in bed until Sunday evening, around 8:30. I finally ate something and went back to bed as soon as I could take more medicine. I woke up around 3 and my fever finally went down to about 99 degrees. I went to work on Monday with a headache but no high fever. As the day continued, my head started feeling better and my breathing improved. I went to bed about 8:00 on Monday evening. It was wonderful Tuesday when I woke up and could take a deep breath! My headache was almost gone. It took me until Friday before I had my energy back.  I had no reaction except a sore arm after my first Moderna shot.  This second shot took me out. If this shot is required yearly, I will opt out! I care not to do this every year!

approximately 3 weeks after the covid vaccination was received, my daughter began not feeling well. LAB_DATA: I took her to urgent care the day after symptoms began (sunday), and they noted her swollen lymph nodes.  They tested her for both strep and mononucleosis, both of which came back negative.  On Monday we performed the Binax at home covid test, which was negative.   She was told that if she wasn't feeling better in a couple of days to see her primary doctor.  She spent most of Saturday, Sunday and Monday in bed with the extreme fatigue and began feeling better on Tuesday and was much better on Wednesday.  We weren't making a connection with the covid vaccine, but today read that there is a connection between lymphadenopathy and the covid vaccine, so I thought I would report it.  In the days following the first dose of her covid vaccine she did not have any symptoms other than a sore arm and a slight red rash that appeared at the injection site approximately 4 days after the shot.  She is scheduled to have her second dose in two days.

They used to be read, but are now brown and oval.  They have left a permanent scar.  It WAS alarming at first, but was ONLY MILDLY itchy at worst, so fortunately it was not painful. I am reporting this because as a Native person I feel it is important to be recorded in case me or other Native or Non Native people get it, since if people continue to get it, they will at least know they are not alone in that.

On Wednesday April 14th I got my second vaccination shot. The following day I had a 103 F fever, body aches, chills, migraine, sore muscles, couldn't walk, excessive thirst. Those effects lasted all day and I felt better on Friday. Saturday night chest pain started along with sore arm getting worse. I took ibuprofen and melatonin to sleep. Woke up Sunday morning and pain came back and gradually got worse until I went into the ER around 9 am. They gave me Morphine to put the chest pain at bay. Then transferred me by ambulance to a different hospital with a cariology department. They treated me as if it was Myocarditis and also got an x-ray of my chest. The next morning I had an MRI and that is what confirmed it to be Myocarditis. I was then discharged with lots of medications to keep the inflammation down.
LAB_DATA: X-ray didn't find and issues. The MRI determined that the cause was Myocarditis.
ALLERGIES: Mild Latex Allergy just a small rash if worn for long periods of time.

client had syncope episode after receiving 1st Moderna Covid Vaccine. Vaccinator gave injection. Within seconds client fainted. Another RN attended to client and immediately transferred to anti gravity chair. Lead PHN informed. Upon arrival client was being put in chair. Pale, diaphoretic, awake. Per client felt was going to vomit. PHN handed client nearest trash can. One vomit episode at 1354. Worker brought client water. Per client already feeling much better. PHN asked client if he recalled what occurred. Per client stated "everything went blurry and when I woke up there was many people around me". RN stated client did not get injured, staff able to intervene. At 1357 vitals: blood pressure 130/70, pulse 70. Per client lightheaded improving, mild nausea. Per client only had breakfast, minimal water intake and had been working outdoors all day. Client stated also having history of fainting with needles. 1404 vitals: blood pressure 110/50, pulse 62, oxygen 97%. Per client feeling much better, able to sit straight on gravity chair. PHN advised client to have someone pick him up. Vitals 1409: blood pressure 112/50, pulse 73, oxygen 99%. Per client does not follow up with provider. Client advised to follow up with provider and ER precautions given. 1416 vitals: blood pressure 100/50, pulse 69, oxygen 99%. Per client all symptoms resolved, waiting on ride. Last vitals at 1424: blood pressure 115/50, pulse 65, oxygen 96%. Client able to stand up with no dizziness. Client left facility at 1429 with steady gait.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: client received 1st Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine. Client was leaving observation room after fifteen mins when he informed RN he was feeling dizzy. RN had client sit down and began taking vitals. 15:52 vitals: blood pressure 142/84; pulse 64; oxygen 98%. Per client had only an orange all day and no water. RN gave client water. Client informed he would stay an additional 30 mins for observation, client agreed. PHN  arrived, client sitting in chair, alert and oriented. Per client no relevant medical history, no medications and no history of allergies. Per client does not follow up with provider and unsure if he has history of high blood pressure. 1557 vitals: blood pressure 138/96, pulse 73, oxygen 98%. Per client starting to feel better. 1602 vitals: blood pressure 141/88. pulse 74, oxygen 98%. Client denied chest pain, shortness of breath, blurry vision, or headache. Client aware blood pressure high. Vitals: blood pressure 146/85, pulse 62, oxygen 98%. Per client headache, pain 1/10. PHN advised to get primary doctor to follow up on high blood pressure. ER precautions also given. Vitals at 1624: blood pressure 143/78, pulse 63, oxygen 98%. No complaints. Last vitals at 1637: blood pressure 139/77, pulse 64. Client left facility with steady gait at 1640.

The patient received BioThrax (anthrax vaccine adsorbed) (dose: 9, lot number: 300070, and expiry date: 26MAY2021) for immunisation. It was reported that a BioThrax vial was opened (first puncture) on 20FEB2021, and the 28-day expiry from the first puncture was on 20MAR2021. On 09APR2021, this patient received a dose of BioThrax vaccine from the same vial. This was series 9 of BioThrax for the patient.   Additionally, it was reported that as per the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC), multi-dose vials are to be discarded 28 days after ?rst puncture. Moreover, the nurse stated that "our specific training and guidance states BioThrax is to be discarded 28 days from ?rst puncture" but there was no information about recommendation to be discarded after 28 days from the first puncture with the product.  Action taken with BioThrax with respect to the reported event was not applicable. The outcome of the reported event was unknown.  Company Comment: A patient received a dose of BioThrax vaccine beyond 28 days from the first puncture of the vial (vaccination error), and further details of the event are limited. When I interviewed pt upon intake, she told me that she had felt faint after previous vaccinations.  She denied any other type of reaction.   My tech and I observed her closely, and she began to complain of dizziness and feeling hot about 5 minutes after receiving vaccine.  I sat with her, gave her water and candy.  She then told me her dizziness was getting worse and asked to lie down.  I took her pulse which was WNL..  She also had some Gatorade.  We called paramedics as a precaution.  They assessed her and she continued to improve.  She was able to sit in a chair and felt fine after 5 more minutes.  She left pharmacy.
PRIOR_VAX: unknown

SYMPTOM_TEXT: My partner felt pain overnight. Then, felt flu like symptoms- plus chills- the next day and night. The following morning at 7:00 am, Patient said that she felt real sick. She also, complained of having a real bad Headache, Not long after that, she felt like throwing up. She tried to throw up. Except, nothing came out and she felt very nauseous because of the vaccine. When she came call to bed, I offered to make her some breakfast to help her feel better.  Unfortunately, she felt, too, I'll to try and eat an food because of the way she felt. So, I laid next to her with the hope that all would be well. Because, the pharmacist who administered the second dose.  Assured my partner, that it was normal to feel flu like symptoms the next day. So, we never doubted what the pharmacist advised. All of sudden, she suffered a cardiac arrest in my presence and died in front of me.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient passed out and ended up falling off the chair hitting his forehead (left side)on the concrete flooring. Patient seemed to be doing okay after being observed by EMS for about 45 minutes. BP 110/74, denied dizziness or nausea but was complaining of headache. Patient's mother refused transport to ER.

Pt received the vaccine in l-deltoid area and within seconds lost consciousness. After being unconscious for roughly ten seconds, pt was arousable by calling his name and lightly shaking him. Pt was seated during his loss of consciousness, was caught by the nurse administering the shot, pt did not hit his head or suffer any trauma. Pt was assisted to a stretcher, given water to drink and his vital signs were monitored. Upon initial assessment, pt was A&O x 4, GCS 15, blood pressure 88/60, pulse 58, pupils equal and reactive to light, lung sounds clear, respirations 16 and non-labored. Pt denied ever fainting before, denied any allergies, medical history, denied taking prescription or over the counter medications, and denied birth defects. Pt was reassessed after about 5 minutes of initial assessment. A&Ox4, GCS 15, BP102/68, PR 78, PEARL, LS clear, RR 16 non-labored. Pt was continuously monitored for 30 minutes and advised to follow up with his primary doctor for an assessment of new-onset syncopal episode.  PT's mood improved and was reassessed for vitals before leaving the clnic. A&0x4  GCS 15, BP 118/80, PR 84, PEARL, LS clear, RR 16-non-labored, PT released from care and exited the site with no further findings.

Patient without medical history, allergies, or medications, arrived with sister for Johnson and Johnson vaccine. Patient received vaccine and then became lightheaded, so the RN called for a medical response. NP and RN responded and found patient lethargic but answering questions appropriately, sitting in a chair. Patient was able to tell me his name, DOB, and what he had for lunch. Patient was moved over to nearby cot and while there experienced a 15 second syncopal event while supine. Patient was hypotensive and diaphoretic. Patient became responsive after 15 seconds and was able to tell us his name. Patient was able to sit up and drink juice, have a granola bar, and inform us that he has experienced this reaction to a flu vaccine and while having blood drawn. Medical team was called to evaluate the patient. The patient refused transport and signed out.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Difficulty operating a motor vehicle at speeds over about 45 mph. I drove to the first vaccination appointment that morning (3/2/2021) and everything was fine. Driving home from the jab I started to experience trouble driving my car when crossing a major bridge in Pittsburgh. The feeling was akin to the anticipatory feeling of being on a climbing roller coaster or drop ride in an amusement park. Elevated heart rate; disorientation and a sort of adrenaline like rush. The feeling returns every time I attempt to drive on a freeway/bridge/etc though local driving is fine. (I was driven to the 2nd jab.) The issue continues now, close to 2 months after it began 45 minutes after receiving the 1st jab. In the several months prior to the jab I was driving extensively with no issues.
LAB_DATA: I am just now going to start looking into treatment. I had anticipated the effects would fade.
HISTORY: High Blood Pressure; Pre-Diabetic; High BMI

SYMPTOM_TEXT: About 15 minutes after my vaccine my lips, tongue, gums, and inside of mouth were itching. I notified the nurse immediately. By the time I was administered a shot of 50mg Benadryl, I had started a slight itching on my arm and legs. My oxygen saturation level (read with meter on finder) was 99%. The nurse listened to my breathing to ensure I was not wheezing. My throat did not swell and neither did my tongue. I was monitored for about 30-45 minutes longer and released with instruction to take Tylenol as needed and Benadryl if needed again. I was instructed to call 911 with any sign of anaphylaxis. I napped during the day but have had no other symptoms other than a mild headache. I had some slight confusion on the way home but that occurs with any dose of Benadryl I take, so the shot of Benadryl could have caused that.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Client received the 1st dose of Moderna COVID vaccine and expiration date 5/22/21 at 1:30PM.  Client reports to EMT  and Nurse dizziness and tingling in her right finger.  Client received vaccine in left deltoid.  PHNs arrive to find patient sitting in chair alert and oriented x 4.  At 1:34pm vitals: blood pressure:172/94 , pulse:84 , and oxygen:98%. Client reports she has no medical history and takes no medications and has no known drug allergies. Client reports eating.  PHN noticed rash on back and PHN noticed rash to face and injection site on left deltoid. PHN  offers Intramuscular Benadryl , which client declined and asked for an oral benadryl.  PHNs offered client water, client accepted water. At 1:36PM  client took oral Benadryl.  Client reports no itchiness, no shortness of breath, client stated she was a little warm and had an itchy feeling in her throat that was starting to go away.  PHN  advised client to not drive due to Benadryl causing drowsiness. Client denies any drowsiness.  At 1:39pm vitals: blood pressure:170/90, pulse:78, and oxygen:98%.  Client reports no trouble breathing and dizziness has subsided.    At 1:44pm vitals: blood pressure: 150/70, pulse:79, and oxygen:97%. PHN notices rash on forehead and back rash started to clear up, client reports no itchiness and no more tingling in her finger and no longer feeling sensation of heat . Client reports "feeling like something is stuck in her throat" PHN  clarifies with client and client denies any shortness of breath.  Provide client with ER precautions and to follow up with her provider.  At 1:49pm vitals: blood pressure:160/100, pulse:82, and oxygen:98%. Client reports no chest pain, no headache, no dizziness, no trouble breathing, no more throat sensation that she had reported earlier.  PHN left to attend to another emergency in vaccination area. RN took over and took vitals at 1:55pm vitals: blood pressure:163/95 and pulse:77.  PHN  returns. At 2pm vitals: blood pressure:160/100, pulse:82, and oxygen:97%. Client denies any shortness of breath, pain, or tingling in fingers and rash is improving. PHN text supervisor with a text and a phone call, unable to contact.  At 2:05pm vitals are blood pressure:162/92, pulse:77, and oxygen:98%. Client denies any shortness of breath, discomfort or pain. Client remains alert and oriented. At 2:10pm vitals are blood pressure:170/98, pulse:74, and oxygen:98%. Client denies any chest pain, dizziness, headache or blurred vision, skin is warm and dry and rash still present but improving. Client remains alert and oriented. At 2:13pm PHN text Lead PHN  that blood pressure still elevated, rash has improved and no other symptoms. Client reports needing to use the restroom PHN  accompany client to restroom. PHN  meets client and PHN in the restroom and review ER precautions again. Client walked out with a steady gait at 2:17PM.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 1 month after my second Covid vaccine, I went to my plastic surgeons office and had dermal fillers done.  2 weeks later I had red blotches (welts) on my face at each spot where the fillers were injected.  I sent pictures and after talking to the nurse injector who conferred with my doctor, I was given a prescription for Medrol and Cipro.  I was seen in the office 2 days later.  Within 10 days my face cleared up. The following week after having finished my meds, my face was inflamed once again.  Called the doctors office and spoke with the nurse who  said they were not  comfortable prescribing a stronger steroid and suggested that I set up an appointment with my primary care physician who I will be seeing tomorrow (April 29).   My plastic surgeon and his nurse thought that maybe the combination of the second Moderna vaccine and the fillers were causing this adverse reaction.
ALLERGIES: Penicillins  Keflex Zithromax  Tetracycline  Iodine Naproxen  Neomycin  Guaifenesin Propylene Glycol

My left shoulder has felt like it was bruised ever since the morning after the vaccine (4/3/2021). Today, 4 wks later,  it still hurts to the touch.

? Tuesday, April 6th ? Patient receives the 2nd Pfizer vaccine shot ? Thursday, April 8th ? Patient is sick with vomiting and diarrhea ? Friday, April 9th ? Patient is delirious and still sick with vomiting and diarrhea. She is also has pain in her stomach.  An ambulance is called to take her to the hospital.  The hospital determines her white blood count is elevated, indicating an infection.  Blood sugar is very high ? approximately 400.  Covid test is negative.  She is restless upon arrival.  She tries to climb out of bed continuously. She is restrained. o Saturday, April 10th ? Patient is running a fever and is in pain.  She is also confused and doesn?t recognize her oldest sister.  Meds are administered to handle both items. (Toradol?).  Blood sugar around 200.  She continuously counts and calls for Mother and Father.   Patient continues to be restless o Sunday, April 11th  - at request of family, a CT scan is done of her stomach and abdomen.  Nothing is found.  Potassium was at 3.2 (normal is 3.5) so she received an IV drip to help with potassium levels.  Sugar ? 206.  Later drops to 176.  Patient calms down some. She is still confused and doesn?t recognize her oldest sister. ? Monday April 12th ? the hospital attempts to do an MRI, but patient panics.    This is a closed MRI and her 1st husband died in one.   The MRI isn?t done. ? Tuesday, April 13th ? she is asked by the doctor to state her name and wiggle her toes.  She complies. Doctor orders speech therapy.  She is sedated for an MRI and a CT scan. Both are successfully completed.  She sleeps for the rest of the day.  Blood sugar ? 274 @ 5:09pm. ? Wednesday, April 14th ? Patient was asleep all day.  Most of the day she isn?t responsive when nurses come in and do things like take blood.  She normally responds even if she is asleep.   Around 5pm she starts to respond and make noises; she briefly opens her eyes then falls asleep.  She continues to run a temperature. ? Thursday, April 15th ? Patient is asleep most of the day.  She is responsive when nurses do things like take blood.  A spinal tap is performed.  There was mention of dementia.  Hospital is sharing little information, varying from she is retreating into herself vs. something worth isolating is going on.  Temp was 102.3 at 7:37, but later dropped to 99.3 without meds.  Dr.  (neurologist) provides an update to the family.  Tests so far are negative.  EEG showed sleeping brain (she was asleep during test).  MRI showed nothing.  Spinal tap negative so far.  No infection or anything has shown up.  Orders another EEG and MRI ? Friday, April 16th ? Patient tried to open her eyes.  ? Saturday, April 17th ? a met code was called on her and she was moved to ICU.  A circulation issue was found in right leg.   Occlusion was really bad.  Initially the doctor was concerned about blood clots.  None were found, just swelling.   Pressure was relieved.  Blood pressure issues.    She was put on 2 blood pressure meds, at least.  She was dehydrated and acidic.  Diabetic ketoacidosis was mentioned.  A cytokine storm was expected. ? Sunday, April 18th ? blood pressure not stable.  She was put on dialysis. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient was due for 2nd dose on 4/27/21, administered second dose early on 4/25/21

At 10:40, the patient went in for her first Moderna vax.  She was slightly nervous since she's not a fan of needles. When she got it a vessel must have been nicked, because she experienced a bit of blood streaming down her arm which surprised us. The nurse wasn't concerned and stopped it quickly and cleaned up her arm.  Got her a new bandaid and she was sent to the chairs in the waiting area to wait her 15 minutes following the vax.    I had to pick up my regular prescription so I got in line while she was sitting there surfing on her phone.  As I got to the front of the line, the patient called me and said she was feeling lightheaded. I immediately left the line, and was there (I was maybe 15 feet away) and was asking how she felt. She said she felt sweaty and like she might pass out.  Right then, her eyes rolled a bit and closed and she went limp. I was able to hold on to her and a customer that was behind me in line and I were able to alert the nurse that gave the vax and the pharmacist. Both immediately came to our aid.  We got the patient on the floor and on her side.  The nurse wanted us to have an epi pen in case, but we all didn't think it was an allergic reaction. We checked her blood pressure and it was low.  Another employee was already calling an ambulance and another was getting her some juice. She was beginning to regain consciousness. She was only out for about 2 to 3 minutes at the most.  Her blood pressure was low, but started to come back to normal pretty quickly.  We had her lay there a few minutes and then sit up. Eventually we moved her to the chair a few minutes later.  Within another few minutes the emts arrived. She had already had answered questions for us like her name, birthday, where she was, etc.  The emts repeated those same questions, asked us what happened and rechecked her vitals.  All were back to normal.  They gave her the option of be transported to the ER, but given that she was feeling back to normal she declined and everybody felt good about that decision.
LAB_DATA: Vital check was given on the scene by emergency services. She had her blood pressure and heart rate checked. Checked her breathing.  Was able to answer questions pertaining to who and where she was.  Recovered quickly.  She's had no issues at all since that event.  The pharmacist did recommend that we submit this to find out if she should go through with the second shot.

Moderna Covid-19 Vaccine 03/11/2021 received first dose of Moderna. By next day, expected flu-like symptoms were apparent such as chills, headache, and body aches. Then, full body muscle twitches and motor tics began. The continue six weeks later. On the 7th day post-vaccine, early AM sleep paralysis/seizure sensation 4-5 times before falling back asleep. When awoken, unilateral weakness (right side). Right eye vision blurry. Right ear muffled. Subjective weakness and numbness in right arm and leg. Went to ER and was admitted under suspicion of TIA or mild stroke. CT w/oC appeared unremarkable. Scheduled for a brain MRI following day (3/19) WWO contrast. Appeared unremarkable, so acute ischaemia was ruled out. Blood work was done repeatedly during stay (CBC, metabolic, CRP, sed rate, urinalysis). Everything was unremarkable. Discharged with instruction to follow-up if symptoms did not improve. The unilateral weakness is intermittent six weeks later. On 4/20, allergist tested against components of Moderna vaccine intradermally. This showed a reaction compared to the negative control. Allergist advised to avoid further vaccination with any of the ingredients in Moderna. Allergist posited that symptoms could be a latent reaction to the allergy, but wasn't sure as prolonged presentation seems unlikely. Future follow-ups: rheumatologist to rule out acute autoimmune reaction, 4/21/21. Neurologist second opinion 5/4/21. Primary care evaluation, as PCP was on leave for several months, 5/19/21.
LAB_DATA: CT WO CONTRAST, 17-Mar-2021, Unremarkable; MRI WWO CONTRAST (SEIZURE PROTOCOL), 18-Mar-2021, Unremarkable

I got the first dose of the Pfizer Covid-19 vaccine at the Medical University. Approximately 10 minutes after administration, an allergic reaction began while I was driving alone in my car. Most notably my blood pressure dropped suddenly, causing me to almost pass out. I stopped driving and my symptoms worsened. Symptoms included shaking, sweating, nausea, confusion, rapid heart rate, red blotchy face, slightly labored breathing, itching and slight swelling of my tongue and lips, anxiety. I could still breathe, so I did not seek treatment, but sat in the parking lot of a medical building for at least an hour for symptoms to subside. Symptoms were acute for about 45 minutes and gradually decreased over four hours. The rest of the day and the next day I felt extremely weak. The following six weeks I continued to have swollen, dry, painful lips every single day and a very itchy rash on my hands and wrists. Occasionally I would wake up with swelling around my eyes. I also had an unusual reaction after eating a salad where my lips swelled even more and became numb, along with an itchy mouth. These long lasting symptoms did not go away until I got a steroid cream from a dermatologist, who denied that my reactions were from the vaccine after talking to me for only five minutes. I just believe that there are many more cases of reactions to the vaccines that have not been reported.
CUR_ILL: No history of severe allergic reactions

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Stroke; MRI showed Pontine Stroke; left arm was weak; her writing looked like a baby's scribble/she cannot write or type; arm was sore; she sounded different; they said her speech sounded slurred; was prediabetic before her hospitalization with her number (A1c) usually being 6.5-6.8. She added that when she was in the hospital it was 7.4; was not able to walk at first; her arm was cold; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable consumer (patient) reported that a 63-year-old female patient received the second dose of BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE, lot number: EN6198), via an unspecified route of administration on 24Feb2021 08:00 (at the age of 63-years-old) as a single dose for covid-19 immunisation. The vaccine was administered at the hospital. The patient medical history included high blood pressure that was diagnosed 2-3 years ago, diabetes; she was prediabetic, heart;cholesterol has been high for about 30 years; since she was in her 30s; all from an unknown date and ongoing. The patient previously received the first dose of BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE, lot number: EL3247) on 02Feb2021 (at the age of 63-years-old) for covid-19 immunization. The patient had no prior vaccination in four weeks. Concomitant medications included rosuvastatin taken for blood cholesterol and takes 20mg once a day prior to stroke and in the hospital they increased it to 40mg once a day and ongoing; ramipril taken for blood pressure and she was prescribed with this medication for a while prior to her stroke. It was discontinued in the hospital. Stated that she did not take it everyday because she was allergic to it; and sitagliptin (JANUVIA [SITAGLIPTIN]) taken for diabetes from an unspecified start date and ongoing and stated that she has been taking for quite a while. On 24Feb2021 she had her second shot. She said that everything was fine that morning; that afternoon her arm was sore. Stated she thought nothing of it. That evening she entertained guest. They were saying she sounded different; they said her speech sounded slurred. She had gotten her vaccine at around 08:00. Again, she didn't think anything about her speech. On 25Feb2021, she got up and did some laundry going up and down the steps. Stated that it was difficult because her arm was still sore. She cleaned the house. At around 15:30 she was doing bills and noticed that her writing looked like a baby's scribble. On 26Feb2021, she noticed that her left arm was weak and was told by her doctor to go to the Emergency Room where they told her she had a stroke. She added that it seemed like her arm was cold for a number of weeks. Stated she was the type to wear t-shirts in the winter because she was always hot. During those weeks she was wearing heavy clothes and was under blankets. She was just now starting to feel more like herself and not so cold all the time. The patient was unable to recall time frame when this symptom began. The events did require a visit to emergency room and physician office. The patient was hospitalized for 4 days due to the events from 26Feb2021 to 01Mar2021. During hospitalization, the patient saw a cardiologist, neurologist, her primary care provider, and the hospitalists who all said it was very suspicious that her stroke happened right after her vaccine. Before she got her second vaccine, she was doing embroidery and everything she normally does; nothing was wrong. They did a CAT Scan that showed nothing. Then the MRI of the brain showed a Pontine Stroke on 26Feb2021. Cardiologist put a heart monitor on her and could not find anything. They were looking for A-Fib or something like that when she was on the heart monitor in the hospital; but it never showed anything irregular. She had a loop recorder implanted to monitor her heart and they haven't found anything wrong on it. She had heart tests, carotid artery tests, ultrasound of her heart and nothing was found on those tests. They pretty much told her in the hospital that they couldn't find a reason for her stroke. She kept asking about the vaccine. They did not rule it out as a cause, but they also did not say it was the cause. All the doctors said they could not pin her stroke on the vaccine. They stated it was suspicious and that they had seen 2-3 other patients with a similar situation. One of the doctor's told her he would not rule it out. They did an ultrasound of her carotids and heart and did not find anything on those tests that would have caused her stroke. She was having lasting effects related to her stroke. Her arm was still sore at times, stated it was a different kind of sore and could be related to all the therapy she does now. The lingering effects after stroke was reported as she was not able to walk at first. She's been doing therapy focused on her left side. Stated that her left side was the dominant side and she cannot write or type. She couldn't do the report online due to the difficulty with typing. She wanted to make sure this was reported. The patient has been doing therapy for 7 weeks, twice a day; and stated she likely still has months more of therapy to try and get her left side back to normal. She said that simple daily duties are difficult. The patient also stated that she was prediabetic before her hospitalization with her number (A1c) usually being 6.5-6.8. She added that when she was in the hospital it was 7.4. She doesn't know what made it go up. Then states she doesn't know if the vaccine made it go up or not. She has a follow up with the neurologist soon. The patient also reported medications she has been taking since her stroke and hospitalization; but not prior to her vaccine which included Amlodipine-Benazepril:  5-20mg once a day and Aspirin: 325mg once a day. The patient stated that stroke and heart problems do not run in her family. The outcome of the events was unknown.

4 days after the vaccine I started having periodic sharp pains in my uterus which made me think my period was coming. 6 days post vaccine I started bleeding lightly and the periodic sharp pains continued. 8 days post vaccine I woke up in the most excruciating pain of my life. The pain continued for hours and I tried my best to breath through it. When I went to the restroom there was only a little blood but large amounts of fleshy tissue began discharging from me. Later that day when the tissue seemed to slow down the pain began to subside to a tolerable threshold (although still more severe than normal). I then began to bleed heavier than any other previous cycle. Normally I have a medium bleed for 2.5 days. This heavy bleeding lasted 6 days. I felt extremely dizzy and weak. Finally when the bleeding stopped I started to feel myself regain strength over the next few days although the sharp intermittent jabs of pain in my uterus lasted about three days after the bleeding stopped. I now am feeling back to normal and recovered. I never went to the ER but came very close to going during that time.

I figured if I choose the Pfizer and had an adverse reaction she would tell me "You should have chosen the Moderna!"  Well, I chose the Moderna and look what happened!! :-D

About 3-4 hours after receiving my second dose of vaccine on 1/30/21, I began to experience side effects including headache, myalgias, and fatigue (which I had also experienced with the first dose of vaccine). I had no nausea or vomiting until around 8-9 pm on 1/31/21. At that time I began to have severe nausea and had 1-2 episodes of emesis before falling asleep. I woke up around 3 am and had another episode of emesis. This continued every 15-30 minutes. I was unable to keep any fluids down as a result. After a couple of hours of this I became lightheaded and began to experience abdominal pain after repeated retching. Sometime between 6 am and 7 am I called 911 and was connected to nursing line. I was advised to go to the emergency department. After vomiting another 2 times I called 911 again and asked for an ambulance to be sent. I vomited again in the ambulance before arrival. Once in the ED I was examined, found to be tachycardic, and started on 1L of IV fluids. I was informed lab tests were being drawn, including pregnancy test, urinalysis, CBC, CMP, and toxicology screen. I was given one dose of Zofran IV. Nausea began to subside, and I was able drink fluids without nausea or vomiting. I was informed that lab tests were unremarkable. Patient was in his usual state of health. On Wed, 4/7/21, at 10:20am, he received the first dose of Pfizer COVID-19 vaccine. No immediate vaccine reactions. He went home, complained of pain at the vaccination site and took a nap because he stayed up late the night before.  On Thursday morning, he woke up with chills and feeling like having a fever. He took Tylenol and then took a nap. On Thursday night, he began to have chest pain but he did not tell his parents.  On Friday, he continued to have chest pain so he told his parents about it. His father told him that if chest pain got worse, they would go to an ER. On that night (Friday) at 1am, he told his parents that he was not feeling well, his chest pain had gotten worse and he wanted to be taken to an ER. He also had abdominal pain, dizziness, disorientation, and he vomited. He was taken to ER where he was found to have elevated troponin of 10. The ER recommended  transferring for further work up and the father drove him to the hospital. At the hospital, he was found to have elevated troponins and NT-proBNP concerning for myocarditis of unclear etiology. He was monitored on telemetry and had no concerning ectopy. He had an echo on admission that demonstrated no structural abnormalities, trivial mitral valve regurge, and normal biventricular systolic function. EKG was unremarkable. Troponins were trended q6h and decreased from 32 -- > 23 -- > 17. NT-pro-BNP decreased from 439 to 322 at discharge.

Patient also mentioned that when she experienced heart palpitations before, a whole work up was ordered and she was referred to cardiology and that nothing was found during the work up after previous experience with heart palpitations. The patient also mentioned that she has been fine, that she has been able to work and walk and that she gets her 10,000 steps every day. The patient reported that yesterday, 13Apr2021, she felt great and could do her normal routine, other than feeling chest pains and palpitations.
