The heart palpitations were really bad last night, 13Apr2021, and that she had difficulty sleeping because of heart rate (couldn't hardly sleep at all). The patient's doctor was scheduling her for an echocardiogram. The patient's doctor did an electrocardiogram (EKG) on her on 08Apr2021 and there was nothing there (normal). The patient also mentioned that after returning from the physician's office, her husband went back and looked at the symptoms from the COVID-19 vaccine information sheet. The patient reported that her husband thought that she needed to call to eliminate everything, that they are trying to figure out why the patient was experiencing the heart palpitations. The patient also mentioned that 2 days ago she got on her treadmill to walk and went for 30 minutes. The shortness of breath wasn't enough that she felt that she needed to run to the emergency room. It just felt like when she would breathe, especially at night as she normally breathes with her mouth closed at night, the patient felt like she had to open her mouth to breathe because she can still feel the pressure in chest. The patient was still experiencing the heart palpitations. The heart palpitations are a little worse because they happen so often. Patient reported that initially, she would have a few heart palpitations and then go for hours with none. Patient reported that now, she was feeling the heart palpitations quite a bit. Patient reported that it feels kind of like a little pressure in her chest and then it'll feel like little flutters. The patient further reported that she experiences a little pressure in her chest when she experiences the heart palpitations. The chest pressure has gotten worse over the past couple of weeks and that she was thinking that it would go away like the first one did. Patient reported that she went to the doctor last week and was given an EKG. Patient reported that the EKG was fine and that her physician was scheduling other tests to make sure it's nothing with her heart. The patient didn't think that the heart palpitations and shortness of breath were from the COVID-19 vaccine, but that her husband looked at the vaccine information paper after her doctor's appointment and said she should call Pfizer. SYMPTOM_TEXT: severe immune response effecting the vestibular system; severe immune response effecting the vestibular system/vestibular neuritis; Overall malaise; ringing in both ears; ragging headache; fever; chills; nausea; hypersomnia from 7-jan-2021 to 9-jan-2021; fatigue/ haven't been able to drive or work since; heaviness; dizziness; vestibular neuritis; This spontaneous case was reported by a nurse (subsequently medically confirmed) and describes the occurrence of ANAPHYLACTIC REACTION (severe immune response effecting the vestibular system) in a 57-year-old female patient who received mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (batch no. 026L20A) for COVID-19 vaccination. The occurrence of additional non-serious events is detailed below.     Concurrent medical conditions included Asthma (esterase induced.) since 1970 and Drug allergy (Sulfa, PCN). Concomitant products included SERTRALINE HYDROCHLORIDE (ZOLOFT) for Anxiety, ESTRADIOL (ESTRACE) for Hormone replacement therapy, OMEPRAZOLE (PRILOSEC [OMEPRAZOLE]) for Reflux gastritis, VITAMIN D NOS for an unknown indication.    On 06-Jan-2021, the patient received first dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) 1 dosage form. On 06-Jan-2021, the patient experienced NEURITIS (vestibular neuritis), HEAD DISCOMFORT (heaviness), DIZZINESS (dizziness) and FATIGUE (fatigue/ haven't been able to drive or work since). On 07-Jan-2021, the patient experienced HYPERSOMNIA (hypersomnia from 7-jan-2021 to 9-jan-2021), HEADACHE (ragging headache), PYREXIA (fever), CHILLS (chills) and NAUSEA (nausea). On 08-Jan-2021, the patient experienced TINNITUS (ringing in both ears). On 09-Jan-2021, the patient experienced MALAISE (Overall malaise). On 26-Jan-2021, the patient experienced ANAPHYLACTIC REACTION (severe immune response effecting the vestibular system) (seriousness criterion medically significant) and VIIITH NERVE INJURY (severe immune response effecting the vestibular system/vestibular neuritis). The patient was treated with Rehabilitation therapy for Anaphylactic reaction and Rehabilitation therapy for VIIIth nerve injury. On 09-Jan-2021, HYPERSOMNIA (hypersomnia from 7-jan-2021 to 9-jan-2021) and PYREXIA (fever) had resolved. At the time of the report, ANAPHYLACTIC REACTION (severe immune response effecting the vestibular system), VIIITH NERVE INJURY (severe immune response effecting the vestibular system/vestibular neuritis), NEURITIS (vestibular neuritis), TINNITUS (ringing in both ears), HEAD DISCOMFORT (heaviness), DIZZINESS (dizziness), MALAISE (Overall malaise), HEADACHE (ragging headache), CHILLS (chills), NAUSEA (nausea) and FATIGUE (fatigue/ haven't been able to drive or work since) outcome was unknown.        The action taken with mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) was unknown.   For mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular), the reporter did not provide any causality assessments.   On 10 Jan 2021 visited Dr. prescribed with antivert and steroids, no improvement prescribed antibiotics and referred to ENT. ENT diagnosed severe immune response to Moderna vaccine effecting the vestibular septum. Started rehab therapy for 2 weeks. Conducted a VNG (Videonystagmography) test ,She was diagnosed with vestibular neuritis secondary to the COVID 19 vaccine. Treatment medication included shot of solumedrol, Zpack, Medrol dose pack. Death Narrative:  Patient was previously tested COVID-19 positive on 3/2/2021, but did not have any other predisposing factors(PMH, allergies, etc.) for experiencing an adverse drug event. The ADR did not occur at the time of the administration of the vaccine nor was there an ADR that occurred between the observation period and the date of death. Patient was admitted with afib with RVR on 2/17/21 and was having a HFrEF exacerbation. HR was controlled during admission and he was discharged on 2/19/21. Patient was hospitalized 4 more times over the next two months for cardiac symptoms with last hospitalization occurring 4/12/21 for hypotension/tachycardia and decompensated heart failure. Patient never recovered and transitioned to hospice before passing on 4/16/21. Patient had a PMH significant for afib s/p DCCV on eliquis, CKD, HFpEF on home O2 2L, PMR on prednisone, known R pleural effusion, Covid PNA in 11/2020 and chronic foley

neuropathy; other serious neurological problems; balance problems; Information was received from a lawyer regarding the case in litigation and refers to a patient of unknown age and gender. The patient was administered zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) (dose, route of administration, lot # and expiration date were not reported) for the long-term prevention of shingles and zoster-related conditions. On or about 28-DEC-2013, patient was administered the zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) in a clinic. Subsequently, patient was treated by providers in for the following injuries resulting from patient's zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX) use: neuropathy, balance problems, and other serious neurological problems. The outcome of the events was not reported. The events were considered to be related to zoster vaccine live (ZOSTAVAX).   Upon internal review, the events of neuropathy and other serious neurological problems was determined to be medically significant.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Dose 2: pruritus after doses 2 and 5; mild facial angioedema; chest and neck urticaria; This literature-non-study case was reported in a literature article and describes the occurrence of ANGIOEDEMA (mild facial angioedema) in a 39-year-old female patient who received mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) for COVID-19 vaccination. The occurrence of additional non-serious events is detailed below.   LITERATURE REFERENCE:  Administration of a Second Dose of the Moderna COVID-19.    Concurrent medical conditions included Allergic rhinitis.   On 05-Jan-2021, the patient received first dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) dosage was changed to 1 dosage form. On an unknown date, the patient received second dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) 1 dosage form. On 05-Jan-2021, the patient experienced ANGIOEDEMA (mild facial angioedema) (seriousness criterion medically significant). 05-Jan-2021, the patient experienced URTICARIA (chest and neck urticaria). On an unknown date, the patient experienced PRURITUS (Dose 2: pruritus after doses 2 and 5). On 05-Jan-2021, ANGIOEDEMA (mild facial angioedema) had resolved. At the time of the report, URTICARIA (chest and neck urticaria) and PRURITUS (Dose 2: pruritus after doses 2 and 5) had resolved.        For mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular), the reporter did not provide any causality assessments.   For dose #1 Medical personnel at vaccination site treated patient's urticaria with 25 mg of oral diphenhydramine.  For dose #1 ER treated patient's angioedema with 20 mg of intravenous famotidine and 125 mg of methylprednisolone. For dose #2 Allergy physician administered graduated dosing of vaccine every 15 minutes. Event of pruritic developed after dose 2 and 5 but no treatment was required. No concomitant medications were reported.  Based on the current available information and temporal association between the use of the product and the start date of the events, a causal relationship cannot be excluded. SYMPTOM_TEXT: 1/11/2021: Within 40 minutes of receiving 2nd dose Pfizer vaccine, began having tingling bilateral arms proximal & distal.  Following day, developed a temperature to 102F which remained x4 days.  Since this time, has had continued tingling of the arms & low grade temperature (99F) & has begun having weakness of her upper extremities only with hypersensitivity to heat, as well as touch, but interestingly having decreased sensation to touch of her fingers, feeling as though she wears gloves, with no weakness anywhere else on her body.  She has also beginning to develop a sense of decrease cognition.  She has been seen by Neurology who felt this was a neurologic hypersensitivity reaction. Initially when she began having complaints following injections/day 1, she was given Benadryl with no improvement beyond causing her to sleep.  Since this time she has also been placed on prednisone with no interval improvement.  Relates no cutaneous lesions beyond mottling of her arms/no frank urticaria dermatitis etc., and has had no GI complaints or cardiovascular sequela.  4/19/21: This 60 y.o., female is referred by MD for evaluation of bilateral hand pain, weakness and numbness starting shortly after the 2nd dose of her COVID vaccine (5 her). The patient has generally been in excellent health.  On Monday, January 11th at 9:20 a.m. she received the 2nd dose of COVID vaccine  (Pfizer), in the left deltoid.  She had no immediate reaction but while driving about 45 min later developed numbness and tingling bilaterally in her face, lips, tongue and hands.  She awakened at about 3:00 a.m. with fever of 102, no abnormal sensations in her face but pain, redness and sensitivity in both hands. Systemic symptoms resolved in several days. Hand symptoms have continued to date.  Pain can range as high as 8/10.  She has marked sensitivity such that if she or someone else touches her hands it is extremely painful.  She sleeps with opera gloves to protect them.  She has not had neck pain but has developed grip weakness and has to use 2 hands to hold a cup of coffee.   She has never had adverse reactions to vaccines in the past.  She has had no immunologic disorders.  She initially saw Dr. who tried a short course of steroids without benefit.  She took gabapentin 200 mg followed by 100 and slept for hours without a change in the pain. NSAIDs have been ineffective.  No other medications have been tried.  She has had nothing to suggest a symptomatic COVID infection.  4/23/21: The patient continues to have bilateral hand sensitivity and temperature lability.  The EMG showed diffusely slow sensory conductions, consistent with the non correctable low temperature of her hands.  Motor conductions were notable for slowing in the right median motor with drop in amplitude proximally but with waveforms that did not suggest conduction block.  All motor terminal latencies and F response latencies were normal.  Overall the study is probably normal within technical limitations but if necessary should be repeated in about a month with her hands warmer.  The nortriptyline was just approved yesterday and the blood tests 2 days ago.  She will start the nortriptyline over the weekend and let me know if it is tolerable or effective.  She will get the blood work done early next week and I will review the results with her. HISTORY:  This patient with bilateral hand dysesthesias and temperature lability following COVID vaccination comes in for neurophysiologic testing.  Notably the nortriptyline was just approved and she has not yet started taking it.  Similar the blood test were just approved 2 days ago and she will have them drawn next week.  Her symptoms have not changed since he was here last.
LAB_DATA: EMG showed diffusely slow sensory conductions, consistent with the non correctable low temperature of her hands. SYMPTOM_TEXT: On Friday, April 9, 2021 PT received the second Covid shot.  The shot was administered in the right arm. About 6:00 pm  on that same day significant pain started, affecting his right arm, elbow, shoulder , and chest.   By Monday 4/12/2021 the pain was so severe he went to  a local clinic  to get checked.  He was  prescribed Naproxen for pain.  He was still in so much pain on Tuesday 4/13 /2021 he went to the ER .  They took him immediately back to check for possible heart attack and blood clot.  After a stay of 6 hours  the tests came back that there was no heart attack  or a blood clot.  He was prescribed more pain medication.  Still not getting any relief from pain and now PT's fingers are going numb, PT went to See Dr.   on 4/15/2021. Dr.  determined that the shot had somehow effected  the nerve endings.  He gave him a dose pack of steroids by pill.   He told him to check back if not better in a while.   The week of April 19 the pain eased up through the day to around a level  3,  to only return at night to a level 10, resulting in more loss of sleep.   PT went back to Dr.  on Friday, 4/23/2021 and received a steroid shot in the hip and a prescription of Gabapentin.  The Dr's opinion was that it could take weeks to get better,  and discussed getting a referral to a neurologist.   Today is Thursday, April 29 and PT's  pain is still constant through the day at about a level 3-4 , but at night the pain level is severe.
LAB_DATA: 4/12/2013  FNP seen pain medicine prescribed 4/13/2013 EKG --blood test for heart attack and blood clot at  Hospital ER  Medication also given at ER on this dat

At 1440hrs the patient received her 2nd dose of Moderna COVID-19 vaccine.  ? At 1444hrs. patient while in the observation area started to complain that she was feeling warm and was nauseous. Observation staff immediately responded to provide supported care protecting her from falling, preparing area for emergency response. Staff verbally alerted supervising RN to respond. RN performed triage assessment. Clinical presentation was cool, pale, diaphoretic, capillary refill < 3 seconds. Appeared at risk for syncope with repeated spontaneous retching / dry heaves. V/S (Vital Signs): BP (Blood Pressure)- 91/63, P (Pulse)- 94, RR( Respiration Rate)- 20, SPO2 (Spot Oxygen Saturation)- 91% room air. Patient reported PMHx (Past Medical History) of no known allergies, DM II (Type two Diabetes Mellitus) controlled with Metformin / Glucophage and baseline systolic BP 125 mmhg. Reported previous intake as "breakfast before my shift started at 0600" and "I have been snacking on roasted nuts through-out the day with a diet pop." Differential diagnosis of anaphylactic reaction vs. hypoglycemia event due to cardiovascular changes from reported baseline, gastrointestinal and integumentary changes as well as PMHx and intake.  ? At 1446hrs emergency response protocol activated due to differential diagnosis. 4gm Sucrose administered sublingual / buccal. Tolerated well despite continued spontaneous retching / dry heaves. Supplemental oxygen need continuously evaluated, SPO2 91-93%. Hydration and further emergency medications prepared per anaphylaxis protocol.  ? At 1451hrs FD (Fire Department) / EMT responded. V/S: BP- 98/65, P- 80, RR- 20, SPO2- 95% room air. Capillary blood glucose 91 mmol/L. Auscultation of lung sounds and heart tones performed, within normal limits. Spontaneous retching / dry heaves stopped, zero emesis. Patient reported that she had a history of syncopal events with injections. Stating "Since, my last big surgery a couple years ago, I have been fine. I get my blood drawn or whatever, no problem."  ? At 1458hrs EMS arrived. V/S: BP- 101/62, P- 70, RR- 18, SPO2- 95% room air. During continued interview, Patient became more readily responsive to questioning. Integumentary changes improved, dry to palpation and color returned to her face. Patient refused to be transported to the hospital for further evaluation stating, "I don't know why this happened, it just happened so fast. I'm sorry."  ? At 1510hrs EMS and FD / EMT returned care of the patient to clinic staff. She was offered hydration and complex carbohydrates. V/S: BP- 101/62, P- 70, RR- 16,  SPO2- 97% room air. Negative for orthostatic hypotension after standing. The patient was assisted to contact her husband who works in the area. ? At 1540hrs the patient was escorted to her husband nearby. She was observed safely entering the passenger side of the vehicle.  ? At 0800hrs 23 April 2021 supervising RN made contact with the patient who reported that she was "feeling well." None of the symptoms had returned and that her injections site did not have any redness, warmth or swelling. She was encouraged to follow-up with her primary care provider and to contact the local healthcare facility with  any needs further needs.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Vaccine was drawn up appropriately. Patient was stuck with needle. At the point of pushing the plunger for injection, the majority of the dose failed to exit through the needle endpoint. Instead, the dose was flushed through the luer-locking spiral between the needle and barrel and dripped onto the floor. Due to very little to no dose reaching the patient, a second dose was redrawn and administered to the patient in the same arm, but area greater than or equal to 2 inches in distance from the original needle stick. Patient verified she felt no administration on first attempt, but definitely felt dose entering arm on second attempt. Used the same arm because there was no guidance from the CLINIC released to used opposite arm in this scenario. Patient confirmed plan to administer 2nd attempt and requested same arm at that time. No issues or significant side effects occurred anytime after actual administration of second attempted dose.

He received the first dose on April 10th at 0900 at a church near his home. 15 minutes after receiving the vaccine he reports experiencing sensation of pins and needs of his tongue, lip and face. He left the vaccine site and the symptoms became more noticeable. 90 minutes after the injection he took Benadryl which resolved his symptoms of pins and needle sensation, but it returned 4 hours later. He continued to take Benadryl every 4-6 hours from the 10th to the 14th until finally he decided to stop by the Emergency Department. There he was given a 5 day course of prednisone (40mg daily) and switched from Benadryl to Zyrtec BID. He reports good symptoms control on the Zyrtec but states that it still doesn?t feel completely resolved. He didn?t feel like the steroids helped at all. If he misses a dose of Zyrtec he feels the symptoms start to worsen again which prompts him to take another dose of Zyrtec. He denies any numbness, tingling, weakness anywhere else on his body. He denies difficulty speaking or swallowing. He has not experienced any syncope, shortness of breath, hives, flushing, vomiting, or diarrhea in conjunction with the injection. The only other time he has experienced symptoms like this was when he was given an IM injection of PCN > 10 years ago. He was then given a one-time dose of Benadryl and the symptoms resolved within an hour and never returned.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On April 1, 2021, I received my 1st dose of the Pfizer vaccine at the Center and the only side effect from the vaccine at that time was localized soreness at the injection site of my left shoulder.   On April 2, 2021, earlier that day the soreness at the injection site began to dissipate after doing push-ups and massaging my left arm. After going to bed last night and that night is when the additional side effects started.  I was awakened by itching on both arms which had formed whelps from my shoulder to my forearm.   For the next 13 days, the whelps and itching were sparsely during the day (which had consumed my legs, upper torso as well as arms) as they presented the illusion to be getting better but would flare up at night while sleeping. I attempted to do home remedies from Calamine lotion, Benadryl and cold showers but nothing seemed to effectively work against the itching and the whelps that resembled Hives.    On April 13, 2021, while at work a new side affect began which was the swelling of my bottom lip (particularly the right half) along with itching in my throat.  The swelling reduced itself as I continued to work through the night but the discomfort in my throat continued. The whelps and itching were still sparsely present as well.   On April 14, 2021, later that morning, post work, the reduced swelling of my lower lip and throat discomfort I decided to go to the ER. While enroute to the ER, my top lip began to tingle and swell. These events made me more concerned about the severity I was experiencing since receiving the vaccine.   After checking into the ER and being triaged, the doctor informed me that I would be hospitalized overnight due to the swelling of my upper lip, elongated tonsils, elevated blood pressure and the diagnosis of whelps as Hives. For the next three nights I was intravenous administered Epinephrine, Benadryl and Prednisone.   On April 16, 2021, the third night I was discharged from the hospital with the same medications and informed to follow up with an allergist.

Patient is a 29 yo F with PMHx of psoriasis who presented for dose #1 of Pfizer vaccine, she received her vaccine without issues and was being monitored for 15 minutes as recommended. Within her first 10 minutes of being monitored patient notified the staff that she felt warm, within one minute from her complaint of feeling warm she had a full general tonic clonic seizure in her chair for about 15 seconds with associated diaphoresis and thready pulse. Seizure activity broke spontaneously and pt was AO x 3. 911 was called immediately, she was transferred to our medical observation area for further monitoring and examination.   Her initial vitals after seizure activity T: 97.5, HR 69, BP 130/77, 02: 98%, BS within first 10 minutes of monitor without food/water was 134.    Exam: GEN: AO x 3 HENT: nc/at, anicteric sclera, EOMI CV: regular, nl s1, s2, no mrg PULM: clear bilaterally NEURO: grossly intact SKIN: clammy   Upon further questioning pt states she had a similar response while in college to Yellow Fever vaccine but never had an evaluation. She has had vasovagal events with other vaccines and blood draws. She denies any neurological history other than seizure like activity with Yellow Fever vaccine.    She states she had an aura with tunnel vision and feeling warm similar to when she had Yellow Fever vaccine.   She denied any nausea, she was alert and oriented x 3 after resolution of seizure activity. She was transported to ED for further evaluation. Report was provided to  at ED.  Seen by Neuro on 4/23/21: Interim History: Patient is a 30 yr, right-handed woman with no significant medical history who is referred for evaluation of an episode of LOC.   The episode occurred on 4/9/2021,10 minutes after receiving the 1st dose of the COVID-19 Pfizer vaccine. She reports feeing anxious after receiving the dose because of the history of having passed out after receiving vaccines. As with the previous events, she felt "hot and clammy" and had tunnel vision before losing consciousness for approximately 15 seconds.  She was told that she "shook all over" for a few second. Upon regaining consciousness, she was oriented almost immediately and was not confused. The episode occurred while sitting.    Patient reports a history of at least 5 syncopal events, since age 12 yr, with 4 of these occurring while sitting and 2 while standing. All of the evens have occurred either after receiving vaccines in 2016 or undergoing medical procedures. Two of the events also include shaking movements but none have been associated with tongue biting, urinary incontinence or post event confusion.    She also reports a  history of episodes of lightheadedness with postural changes but denies palpitations, CP or SOB.  She has never had a neurological or cardiac evaluation.    There is a history of a mild concussion while playing soccer. There is no history of CNS infections, febrile seizures or family history of neurological disease. No rashes or skin lesions.  Peripheral pulses intact throughout. Mental Status: Orientation: Alert, oriented to time, place and person. Memory: Remote and delayed recall intact.. Language: Speech fluent. Able to name, repeat and follow three step commands.   CN: II: Full visual fields, fundi normal, PERRL.  III, IV, VI: EOMs full, no nystagmus. V, VII: Facial sensation and movement intact. VIII: Hearing intact. IX, X: Palate elevates normally.  XI: Normal.  XII: Tongue midline.    Motor: Normal bulk and tone. 5/5 power throughout. No pronator drift. FFMs quick and accurate bilaterally.    Coordination:  Normal FTN.  No tremor.   Sensation intact to light touch in all 4.    Reflexes:  3/4 and symmetric throughout with downgoing toes.   Gait: Normal, including tandem   Romberg: Negative   Assessment Patient  is a 30 yr old woman with a recent episode of LOC that is consistent with convulsive syncope, despite occurring while sitting, 10 minutes after receiving the first dose of the COVID-19 vaccines. She has a history of similar episodes occurring after vaccinations or medical procedures. She reports episodes of pre-syncope and postural lightheadedness. She does not have risk factors for epilepsy and the episodes have an atypical duration for convulsive seizures.   In my opinion, the recent event is not an allergic reaction to the vaccine and there is no contraindication for receiving the 2nd dose. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient hospitalized within 60 days of receiving a COVID vaccine

After first vaccine: History: Moderna COVID vaccine on 3/11/2021. Arm soreness over the first day or two but nothing else that really struck her. A few days after she started to notice axillary pain that progressed up her right neck and down to her right hand. She saw a physician who thought she was having nerve pain brought on by the vaccine. Around the 18th she started to feel a snapping pain in her wrist. Went to ED on the 20th because she started to have arm shaking, she was given ativan, her arm shaking stopped and they discharged her home. That evening her fingers felt clenched. On the 21st she woke up in the morning, went to urinate and dropped to the floor because her legs felt like jello and felt like they kept giving out. They initially thought the ativan was just making her feel out of it. They waited until the evening but then needed to go to the ED. The concern was GBS and transverse myelitis. They ate dinner and decided to drive to ED, on the drive she was kind of falling asleep periodically. Then she suddenly couldn't lift her water bottle. She started to be completely out of it, Mom says she wasn't responding. Pt says that she felt like she knew what was going on, felt a little out of body and wasn't quite responding. Mom couldn't get her out of the car, she was carried into the ED and at that point she started to recover a little bit more. About 10 minutes later she started to feel better. She was admitted because she was still having trouble walking. In the hospital she had a normal CT head and video EEG but she didn't have any events while on the monitor. Discharged home the following day with the diagnosis of functional neurologic disorder and instructions to establish care with an adult PCP. They advised considering CBT as well.  Since discharge her legs feels tired, going up the stairs feels much harder than it should. She has not had any falls and no longer feels like she is going to fall.  She follows with a therapist, has had dissociative episodes and panic attacks in the past.   Assessment:  20 YOF with PMH of panic attack, POTS, IDA and benign heart murmur who developed weakness of b/l LE and altered consciousness approximately 10 days after her first dose of Moderna COVID vaccine. Also had an episode of unilateral arm shaking the day prior that resolved with ativan in the ED. At this point unclear if directly related to vaccination. Differential includes mild Guillain-Barre 2/2 previous infection or vaccination, stress reaction/anxiety, POTS complication, myasthenia gravis, tick bite, infection, heavy metal poisoning, B12 deficiency, seizure disorder, atypical migraine. Functional Neurologic Disorder diagnosed by neurology after overnight admission  for video EEG which captured no events. CT head  also WNL per neurology discharge summary. Neurologic exam today WNL.   After Second Vaccine: History: She had her 2nd vaccine on 4/15 (6 days ago). Had vaccine in right arm again, she did have some arm pain again. She had coffee without breakfast in the morning. Had finished her first virtual class, went to the restroom during her second class, felt strangely in the restroom, went back to her room. She then passed out. Her fall was unwitnessed. She called to her roommate when she came to but her roommate hadn't heard the fall. She thinks she was only out for a few seconds but cannot be sure. Called her Mom who advised her to eat something so she ate an orange sitting on the floor. She got up to make herself breakfast and she passed out again. Again unwitnessed but patient thinks it was very fast. She crawled over to the couch, sat on the couch for for 15 minutes then felt fine for the rest of the day. She did not feel nauseous at all. She denies palpitations, difficulty breathing and chest pain.  Today in office after orthostatics and blood draw she fainted again, only out for seconds. BP elevated immediately after the event but WNL minutes later.  These syncopal episodes reminded her of her syncopal episodes with IDA and POTS. They do not feel like the episode after the first vaccine when she lost feeling in her legs and was very out of it.  She feels like her arm pain from the first vaccine never fully resolved. After the arm pain worsened from the 2nd shot she tried a 3 day course of aleve to see if that helped things. At this point it is mostly just her right wrist that is painful. Overall feels more localized to wrist than prior. She has since stopped the aleve, last was last night. She has not noticed redness or swelling in wrist or arm.  LMP was 4/2-4/6. She went almost a year without menses so stopped her OCP, but her menses have returned recently and she has restarted OCP.  Assessment: Right arm pain persisted from the first vaccination but otherwise sx had resolved. She got 2nd vaccination on 4/15, only arm pain but yesterday had 2 brief syncopal events and one today in the office. Orthostatic BPs not completely convincing for orthostatic hypotension today.
LAB_DATA: CBC w/ diff, CMP, TSH, B12, folate WNL.  Mild iron deficiency anemia.  CT head and video EEG WNL.

She got the vaccine, and had no reactions at all other than perhaps a chill.  About  2-3 weeks later on 3/7/21 she started experiencing what they are calling muscle confusions.  She feels a tapping sensation on her biceps and triceps and then starts with muscle cramps running down her right arm creating her fingers to cringe or come together or contract.  This then travels down to her right leg to her quadriceps which cramps and convulse and travels to her calves which tighten up like a Charlie Horse and down her toes to where they contract as well.  They are intermittent, scattered and sporadic.  Sometimes she will get 2-3 a day, and then none at all and then a few days later a couple more.   These contractions last 3-5 minutes.  She had COVID back in April of 2020 and was hospitalized until August of 2020 with that.  During that time she was on a ventilator for 60 days and on a breathing tube and coded and was out for about 30 minutes.  She had an EEG of her brain in September and told that she was fine.  her neurologist felt she should have another one due to these symptoms, and she had that and everything was normal.  The doctor prescribed 500 mg twice a day of Levetiracetam.   The seizures kind of regress a little and then they came back and he upped that medication to 1000 mg twice a day.  The seizures still continue and have continued but is still taking the medication.  He felt that she should know see an epileptic specialist and they have an APT for 5/27/21.   These episodes are exhausting and wear her out.   She was going to PT due to the weakness from being in the hospital for so long, and now she is fearful if she is going to fall and uses a walker and is having a setback in that progress.  She is to continue therapy at home for now and to follow up with the Epilepsy specialist.
OTHER_MEDS: Vitamin D, iron, Metformin, Omeprazole, Trazadone, Losartan, Melatonin, Vitamin C, Vitamin B12, calcium.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 50 y/o male, with past medical history of HTN, who presents with dizziness, palpitations and diaphoresis onset post vaccination. Patient states that this is his first vaccination in the two-dose series. Patient received the vaccination to his R arm. NP and Paramedics at patient side. Patient provided with bottle of water and legs were elevated. Patient initial BP was elevated, 159/96, but states that is normal for his history of Hypertension; all other vitals within normal limits (97% RA, 78 HR, Resp 14). Patient glucose was 131 but states that he had a protein shake prior to arrival. Approximately after 10 mins of observation patient stated that he was getting better but then developed chills and palpitations continued. Patient at this time placed on stretcher and was moved to a private area. EKG was obtained and patient noted to be Sinus Tachycardia with HR of 111. Patient with diaphoresis again and BP increased to 158/104. It was determined at this time by the NP that patient needed to be transported to the ER. Fire rescue arrived at site. Patient was evaluated, EKG was obtained and normal. Patient stated that he felt better, and all symptoms resolved. Patient stated that he did not wish to be transported to the ER. Patient signed out AMA with Fire Rescue as well as with the NP. CNO and PM aware.

Patient received vaccine at 2:15 pm at Public Health clinic. She waited the appropriate 15 minute observation period and was feeling well. She then came to PCP office for a routine medical exam and reported feeling well when she first came, although her blood pressure was slightly elevated but pulse was normal. She was taken to an exam room and left for approximately 5 minutes, at which time she presented to the nurses station reporting that she thought her tongue may be swelling. Nurse evaluated and got NP to evaluate immediately. Patient reported she could still breath normally and swallow but that she was still feeling the swelling increase. At this time NP left to get PCP while nurse elevated HOB as patient began to choke on her tongue. PCP ordered epinephrine, 1 mL administered immediately. 911 called. Patient reported she was starting to feel better, swelling began to decrease. She then started to feel shaky, was pale and diaphoretic. She lost consciousness for approximately 10 seconds and pulse was not palpable. Staff readied for CPR and AED brought to room but patient regained consciousness prior to any care being necessary. She began to speak in full, clear sentences and was alert and oriented. 2L o2 applied. She was speaking with staff normally for around 5 minutes while awaiting ambulance, began to feel hot and felt her heart racing. Her PCP advised her that this was a normal sensation brought on by epi. As EMS arrived, patient reported feeling intense chest pain radiating down left arm, intense headache, and tingling in her fingers. As she was being transported to stretcher, patient experienced a 1.5 minute seizure followed by an episode of vomiting. She then left the building via ambulance and was take to Hospital emergency department. There it appears that she received 2 more rounds of IM epinephrine, IV epi, CPR, and was intubated. She was transferred from there to ICU where she is currently admitted on ventilation under sedation and receiving cardiac testing due to continued hypoxia and tachycardia.
LAB_DATA: BMP, Lactate, phosphorus, magnesium, arterial blood gas, BNP. Pt/INR, CBC, troponin, CMP,  D Bili, COVID PCR, Blood culture, TSH, Xray, EKG, Echo

My ears, particularly my right ear, started ringing some throughout the day, which is not normal for me. But it would last a minute or so than go away.  By the next day, arm is only a little tender to touch, can move it around normally, I don't feel tired, my ears are not ringing, and sneezing/coughing gone, still a bit of runny nose. Will not deter me from getting 2nd shot, and was not difficult to deal with side effects, pretty much expected them.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 12 hours after my shot (April 24, 2019) I had a very sore arm much like most people I've talked to but then I had the sensation of being really cold - enough that I couldn't sleep, so I got up and put a heating pad on and numerous layers of cold. Was able to sleep that night. Then on April 28th at around 11:00 pm I got the same sensation but much more significant. It felt like my entire legs were frozen. They were not cold to the touch but the sensation in my skin was that they were very very cold. I could not warm up. 3 shirts, pants, wool socks, 2 blankets - one of them a down comforter - a microwave heated pad and an electric heated pad and I still felt very very cold. No shaking or shivering. No fever. No sweating. My temperature was 97.7 which is what it usually is. Eventually fell asleep but when I got up in the morning (April 29) the cold sensation remained and is now in my arms as well. Took a hot shower but still can't "feel" warm. Sat under multiple blankets and started sweating but never felt hot or even warm. Still no change in temperature and no shivering. Just a very cold sensation - like someone has blasted my legs and upper arms with an air conditioning unit. As of 10:15am on April 29th, these symptoms remain unchanged.
OTHER_MEDS: cyclobenzoprene unisom magnsium powder drink ashwaghanda tincture

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Within 30-minutes of vaccination, the patient reported a headache, slurred speech, and right side weakness. EMS evaluated the patient on-site. The patient was hypertensive (197/129) with a FSBG of 95mg/dL. During stroke assessment, the patient had new onset facial palsy/droop and need speech abnormality which signaled a stroke alert. 12-lead EKG was unremarkable. EMS transported the patient to Emergency Department. In the ED, the patient presented with a headache, chest heaviness, and slurred speech, but no aphasia. NIH stroke scale was 0. Patient remained hypertensive (170/109). Labs, tests, and imaging did not indicate rtPA administration. ED physician administered 0.4mg SL Nitroglycerin, 10mg IV Hydralazine, and 325mg PO Aspirin prior to admission for suspected Transient Ischemic Attack. Upon admission, differential was TIA vs. CVA vs. ACS. Admitting physician ordered HbA1C, lipid panel, MRI brain, CTA head/neck, 2D echo, and neurology consult. Throughout course of admission, patient had recurring midsternal chest pain that was relieved with Nitroglycerin. Imaging ruled out CVA. Given elevated TGs and Cholesterol, patient was started on Atorvastatin 40mg PO. Suspected TIA and ACS.  Neurology consult reviewed the labs and imaging, and stated the episodes of stuttering are most commonly associated with anxiety or stress reaction. Neuro did not recommend any further workup unless this happened again unprovoked. Patient was discharged after a 3-day admission with diagnosis of cerebrovascular disease, unspecified. The patient was prescribed 81mg PO Aspirin, 20mg PO Lisinopril, and 40mg PO Atorvastatin.

BRIEF OVERVIEW:  Discharge Provider: MD Primary Care Provider at Discharge: MD  Admission Date: 4/22/2021;  Discharge Date: 4/23/2021  Active Hospital Problems - Admitted for bilateral PE ? Acute pulmonary embolism without acute cor pulmonale, unspecified pulmonary embolism type (HCC) 04/22/2021  DETAILS OF HOSPITAL STAY: Patient is a 87 y.o. male with psoriatic arthritis, essential hypertension who presents today with right-sided chest pain.  He reports onset starting yesterday. The pain radiated around to his back into the center of his chest. Thought he had pulled a muscle was having heartburn. Taking a deep breath made the pain worse. He tried Tums but no significant relief. It was not associated with shortness breath. Denied any, lower extremity swelling or calf pain.  Today the pain was acutely worse so presented to the emergency department for evaluation. No prior DVT, PE, no FH of DVT/PE. No weight loss. No recent prolonged trip. On arrival to the emergency department his pulse was noted to be elevated to 120 but otherwise vitals unremarkable.  CT angiogram thorax had significant findings of multiple bilateral pulmonary emboli involving segmental and subsegmental vessels.  There was no evidence of right heart strain.  He was started on heparin drip and transferred to another facility for ongoing care. He was switched to Eliquis 10 mg bid for 7 days, then 5 mg bid for 3 months.  He has not sign of any malignancy, no weigh loss. He received Moderna COVID-19 vaccine on 3/4/21 and 4/1/21. It is conceivable that this PE could be complication of COVID-19 vaccine. He should follow up with PCP in 1 week.              CTA also showed partial visualization of gas fluid collection within the right upper quadrant, likely reflecting a duodenal diverticulum which was present on 8/20/2012 CT abdomen, incompletely assessed. There is a small hiatal hernia. PCP to follow. Discussed with wife, and with daughter over the phone.  Patient discharged home.

HISTORY: psoriatic arthritis, essential hypertension, hyperlipidemia, GERD

Initially, I had a resurgence of the same symptoms I encountered during COVID--nothing respiratory, but fever, severe aches, headaches...  Then a few weeks later, I began bleeding...heavily.  This occurred while taking active birth control pills (not at a time I should have been menstruating).  The bleed was extremely HEAVY, large clotted surges.  Cramping was moderate... I don't typically experience cramps with my cycle..  This occurred over 3-4 days.  I consulted with my OBGYN and she recommended I stop taking the pill for 5 days and restart.  During that time, the bleeding subsided and then restarted, 2 times (stopping for over 24 hours) then occurring again with a slight decrease in the amount of bleeding each time.  I have since resumed taking the pill and all bleeding has stopped.  I chalked this up to menopause and stress however recently read articles about the vaccine causing  unusual bleeding patterns and though I would report the event after learning that such data was not collected during trials.

In a nutshell, patient was fine, got the first shot of the Moderna Vaccine on 3/24/21, then began to exhibit many covid-like symptoms starting around 4 hours later but 3 times nasal swap tested negative for COVID19 including before and after vaccination. Suffered with various attempts at treatments and tests for approximately a month and then was admitted to the ER at hospital on 4/28/21.  Wife (former smoker who lives in same house and has lung problems) who took the vaccine at the same time from the same lot suffered minor arm pain, aches and pains and fatigue but was fine the next day.  Patient (59) had normal blood pressure and clear lungs in good health, non-smoker, good weight, exercises regularly and strenuously, good diet, rarely gets ill. He works as a ship?s captain and engineer and has worked in boatyards for years doing physical work. Has tintinnitis and in one eye, glaucoma drops but is on no other prescription medicines. Details: March: had nasal congestion, cough and suspected bronchitis, aches and pains, no fever, PCR tested negative for COVID19, and was treated with antibiotics (azithromycin and then a run of amoxycillin), proair, advair discuss a couple of days, various vitamins/minerals, over the counter cold/flu medicines. Seemed to work with most symptoms going away prior to Marcch 24, 2021. March 24, 2021 morning: Got first shot of the Moderna Vaccine at pharmacy. Lot 045A21A at same time as spouse. That morning had no cough and felt ok. Approximately 4 hours later, patient started to cough, felt congested, felt like flu/pneumonia, trouble breathing, aches and pains especially in joints, extreme fatigue, headache, (but suffered no loss of taste or smell throughout 3/24-present) took Theraflu and went to bed early, slept well. Following days, struggled with intensifying symptoms. Felt like the vaccine gave him covid symptoms without the loss of smell/taste.  Spouse experienced minor pain at point of injection, some fatigue, aches and pains which went away by end of next day 3/25/21. Spouse had some lingering cough left over from earlier bronchitis before getting the vaccine which cough/congested breathing continued with no noticeable change. [Spouse was also not adversely impacted by the second shot of Moderna vaccine a month later.) Apr Wk1 & Wk2: Increasing difficulty sleeping due to lung congestion or suddenly waking up wide awake for no reason. At end of Wk2, had some minor tremors in muscles for a couple of days. Suffered from extreme fatigue, congestion, trouble breathing, nightmares, aches and pains. Took azithromycin run then a run of amoxicillin, proair, prednisone, albuterol nebulizer, occasional Theraflu or over-the-counter cold/flu medicines, vitamins/minerals (including heavier doses of Vitamin D, Zinc, C, etc.), probiotic acidophilus, tonic water with quinine or Perrier, melatonin 10mg and magnesium 500mg at night, occasionally a Unisom sleeping pill. Started to lose appetite where rarely hungry. Would force himself to eat anyway, but occasionally vomited it up. Apr Wk3 4/13/21: Patient got another PCR covid test which was negative, chest xray, blood work done at Urgent Care. Showed some elevated liver/kidney enzymes and low red blood cell count/anemia, vague thickening of the plura, swollen lymphnode in the chest xray, no sign of cardiovascular issue. (Some yellow flags but nothing flashing red.) Dr. recommended followup tests and bloodwork and that he get GI/Cardio/pulmonary workups w/specialists. Patient continued to take antibiotics, pregnizone, albuterol nebulizer, vitamins/minerals, and occasional cold/flu/cough medicines, etc. Added SuperB Complex. One day he had hot/cold chills for a few hours. Apr Wk4: While lungs felt clearer, still coughing and now occasionally vomiting productively or dry heaves, insomnia grew into bigger issue with hallucinations not just with nightmares but occasionally during the day where it was difficult to separate reality from dream, trouble remembering, started to feel paranoid/irrational sometimes, trouble sleeping was not due to lung congestion but more due to panic-attack like heavy breathing or sudden central chest/sternum pain (maybe from coughs), aches in joints, but biggest problem was extreme fatigue and tiring when walking up a flight of stairs, etc. Took some Tramadol occasionally for pain relief (but never with aspirin, Tylenol or cold medicine). Could be sitting comfortably watching a mellow tv program but suddenly need to breathe really heavy, hyperventilating and felt need to standup and walk around until it eased. Extreme trouble sleeping. Most comfortable position was kneeling with body bent over a pillow on the bed. [He'd never had panic-attacks/heavy breathing issues before the Moderna shot and doesn't abuse substances.] Wk5: 4/24/21 feet swelled up and turned purple on the soles. Went for a walk around the block and raised feet. No longer on antibiotics or pregnizone, only taking the albuterol nebulizer, vitamins/minerals/probiotics, melatonin and a OTC cough/flu medicine before bed. Knelt for hours while trying to sleep. 4/25/21, feet more swollen with fluid and more discolored. When searched online, they looked like "covid toes". Took no medicines except nebulizer and took only a couple of vitamins/calcium-vitaminD and before bed a beer, melatonin, magnesium & nyquil. 4/26/21, feet less swollen and no longer purple except a small line on the side of one foot. Patient indicated he had not knelt when trying to sleep prone during night. But only got a couple of hours of sleep, nighttime hallucinations and panic-breathing attacks. Daytime inability to focus, extreme fatigue, aches and pains, quick to tire on any exertion, vomiting food or dry heaves 2 or 3 times that day, panic-like-attacks with need to heavy breathe/hyperventilate. Wheezing with occasional rattle at end. Coughs sometimes productive, sometimes not but lungs didn?t feel very congested and oxygenation/blood pressure was good. 4/27/21, went to work in morning and was able to perform but very tired. In early afternoon, came home, ate, took nyquil and nebulizer and tried to sleep. 4/28/21, felt much worse, feet and knees swollen, extreme exhaustion, felt miserable. Went to work anyway. Came home around 2pm, ate. Felt much worse so we went to the ER at Hospital. Spouse provided MMC with his medical conditions, medicines, the info on COVID IGG serology test and informed them of the chest xrays and bloodwork that had been done at the Urgent Care center 2 weeks prior. ER indicated he needed to stay overnight and they performed additional bloodwork, xrays, scans and MRIs. The ER doctor called in specialists in Nephrology and Cardiology to provide consultations.
OTHER_MEDS: Only prescription was glaucoma eye drops. Took a multivitamin that morning and had cheerios for breakfast.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Recipient is a 17yo who presented for second dose of COVID-19 vaccine. She reported some anxiety related to receiving dose #2, and had some nausea after dose #1. She was alone as a driver of her own POV.  Consent was obtained from the recipient and her custodial grandparent by phone, witnessed by doctor. She initially did well after the vaccine, but after approximately 5 minutes began to complain of feeling nauseated, lightheaded, and tingling extremities (hands and feet). She was noted to be hyperventilating, and was placed in a supine position but continued to feel some lightheadedness and difficulty breathing. Breath sounds were clear without wheezing noted, HR 70s with RRR. She was noted to have ongoing anxiety, nausea and symptoms progressed and although she remained normotensive to hypertensive (initial BP 128/74), she had repeated episodes of syncope.  She was transferred to the ambulance and further vitals and EKG were obtained. She had some confusion after episodes of syncope and some seizure-like activity with syncope, with very brief episodes of LOC, with noted tachycardia with HR up to the 140s during episodes of syncope.  BP ranged 129/86 to 140/84. IV access obtained and she was given NS and started on oxygen at 2 liters, but saturations remained in the 98-99% range. She was ultimately transferred to the local ER for further evaluation and management given ongoing symptoms, evaluated at hospital.
LAB_DATA: EKG with NSR and sinus tachycardia, HR 102, no concerning ST or T wave changes.

Pt was found to be in acute liver failure in the ED w/ AST and ALT > 1000. Lactate > 15.0. BMP showed AKI on CKD and BG >500. Pt did have cardiac arrest while undergoing CT Scan and ROSC was achieved after CPR x 20 mins.  Pt was hence transferred to the ICU for higher level management and admitted for cardiac arrest and acute liver failure.   Upon arrival, Pt was intubated and sedated. Pt was started on insulin gtt for DKA and was started on Levophed for low BP.  Pt underwent cardiac arrest shortly after arrival to the ICU. CPR was performed for > 20 mins without ROSC. Family arrived at bedside and decision was made to stop CPR at 0205 on 04/29/2021.

I received my shot at about 4:15PM on April 22, 2021. Roughly thirty-five minutes or so after receiving the vaccine, I started to have numbness and tingling in my lips. It slowly spread to my tongue, the top of my throat, and on the muscles of my face--from the bottom of my chin and jaw up to my eyes. This spread took about two hours. The numbness would get stronger and fade, get stronger, and fade. The numbness lasted through the evening and was still present when I went to bed.   In the morning the numbness was gone. I had a small bit of numbness start up in my lips at some point that morning, but the numbness only lasted maybe two minutes before going away completely. It did not return.  My body ached quite a bit, but I had no other adverse affects: no fever, no rash, I could still swallow and breathe just fine.  I did not report until now because I have a sulfur sensitivity that sometimes flares up with similar numbness symptoms. I did not know if this flare up was due to other causes, not the vaccine, and I didn't want to cause confusion. But since the flare up happened so soon after the vaccine and I had no other sources of sulfur (I ate much earlier in the day, my usual source of sulfur flare ups), it is possible that the vaccine was the cause, and my family rightfully encouraged me to report it.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine EUA I had COVID at the end of March. My quarantine and symptoms ended 4/9/2021. Per CDC guidelines, you are able to receive your first COVID vaccine 2 weeks after. I received mine on 4/24/2021. It was the sickest I ever remember being, sicker than when I had COVID. I had a fever above 100 degrees for 36 hours. My fever spiked to 102.6 and 102.7 degrees several times during that period. My body hurt so bad that you couldn't touch my skin. I could barely move for 18 hours during this period. I could only move my hands and mouth because my body hurt so bad. I could even reach for water on my own. My fever and body aches did not go away until late Monday afternoon around 5 PM. I am a very strong, active and fit 43 year old woman who exercises daily. I have never felt this poorly.

First dose on 3/5/2021 received with minor issues of slight pain in injection site later, but also some tingling in injection site. SECOND DOSE on 4/2/2021 was a different story.  About 15 hours later at 3:00 am I woke up with 100.5 fever, SEVERE pain at injection site (like someone had punched me in the arm and bruised my arm), and SEVERE level 9 (out of 10) pain in all joints in my hand and two big toes.  Fibromyalgia muscular pain SEVERE level 9.  Headache, SEVERE fatigue - could not get out of bed very well.  SEVERE brain fog - I could barely think logically.  I tried taking 50mg full spectrum CBD oil to avoid taking an NSAID (I was concerned it would affect proper immune response).  At 6:29 am the fever was lower, but I could no longer take the pain, so I took 400mg Ibuprofen (Advil).  4-6 hours later took another 400mg Ibuprofen (Advil) and stayed in bed and slept several times that day.  For the next two days the severe brain fog and severe fatigue remained.  I continued to take 400mg Advil as needed.  The brain fog was so severe that if I picked up my keys (or any other object), I would immediately ?lose? them and not know where they were because I had placed them somewhere else and could not remember anything.  I stayed home for at least 72 hours due to the fatigue and the fear of driving and possibly getting in an accident.  It seems the high severity of the issues lasted 72 hours, but all of the above reported issues continued for several weeks at a lower severity - with fatigue being the worst - requiring one or two naps per day.  As of today, April 29, there is still slight pain in all hand joints and some fatigue, but there seems to be gum issues (hurting) since about April 26th.  I am brushing my teeth lightly, using ?Smart Mouth? zinc oral rinse, and sucking/chewing on a whole clove every once in a while for pain relief and for the anti-biotic properties.  I did not contact my physician because I read online that people with Fibromyalgia have worse side effects and I figured the effects would subside over time.  I have an upcoming appointment with my doctor on May 26, 2021 at which time I will report these side effects and my strong concern about any future booster shots and the severe side effects I may encounter.

Began on 3/26/21 with numbness in face. Woke up on 3/27 with numbness in feet. Spread to my feet and up legs and arms through next couple days. Fatigue increased dramatically, though it was present prior. Dizziness, sharp pains in left ear in skull, nerve issues. The following is a log from when the symptoms became most intense, so significant I have not been able to drive myself and been working from home due to balance issues, no feeling in feet, and neurological symptoms. After different a week and a half,, i sought medical care and began logging daily as follows:   Fri 4/9: fatigue was high, neuropathy present. Balance was off. Stabbing sharp pains into the left ear but behind the ear in head. Dizzy spells with static feeling rush in forehead lasting a few seconds and passing. Gate while walking feels awkward and difficult. Think walking after sprinting on a treadmill plus's stiffness   Sat 4/10: couldn't eat. General malaise. Fatigue. Neuropathy and balance issues present. Gate slightly improved. Noted increase in joint pain and popping in wrists elbows hips and knees. Needed white noise to cover ear ringing to sleep.   Sun 4/11: feeling a bit better. Able to eat. Gastric issues after eating. Slightly more energy but neuropathy and balance was frustrating like superglue on my fingers and areas of my feet with no feeling at all surrounded by pins and needles. Aching in wrists and pain shooting down through to heel of my foot. Ear ringing more noticeable. Two instances of ice pick ear pain.   Monday 4/12: neuropathy present, balance improved. No digestive issues. Feeling more stable while walking. Still numb in hands and feet and part of my face but less pronounced. Ear ringing unbearably loud and constant.   Tuesday 4/13: slightly less energy but neuropathy still seems improved and not losing balance as much. Ears obnoxious, joints popping and cracking constantly. Pain in wrists and hands. One instance of ice pick ear pain   Wednesday: same as Tuesday, but no ear pains. Had to take a nap in the middle of the day due to worn out feeling. Laying in bed felt something in my back snap, then a stabbing pain into my lower right side of my back. Aching like the skin was hurting for hours.    Thursday: other symptoms same as Tuesday. Ears ringing crazy loud, stiff in the hips more noticeably. Neuropathy present with dizzy waves/vertigo. Low back skin pain right side continue. Also right hip. Gate while walking is starting to feel like it did before after a few days of improvement.   Friday: back still hurting. Neuropathy increased. More numbness than previous few days. Very stiff throughout lower back hips and legs. Low back pain. Gate while walking feels awkward and robotic. Ears ringing. Joints throughout cracking/popping. This is not historically common for me. While washing dishes got shooting pain down my left wrist back of hand almost shooting down the veins to in between my pointer finger and thumb. Painful to touch. Immediate strong increase in the pins and needles in my hand concentrated in finger tips but now radiating up forearm too. .numbness in feet and part of my face. Whole body aching. When trying to sleep kept getting head rush static attributed to Benadryl to sleep and staying up too late.   Saturday: very tired. Back hurting in morning. Felt better after getting up. Kept feeling head rush like static in forehead continuing on and off throughout the day into the night with dizziness almost like I might pass out. Nausea and low appetite Fatigue higher than normal. Neuropathy still present. Ears ringing insanely loud and constant. Aching and stiffness in hands wrists and legs and feet in heel/sole. Chest pain in sternum. Had a few months ago almost daily for awhile. Went away til now.   Sunday- neuropathy the same. Ears ringing the same. Stiffness throughout. Dizzy spells and static in forehead. Nausea and low appetite. Fatigue. Ice pick ear pain starting in evening a few times throughout the night.   Monday. Neuropathy the same. Ears ringing the same. Slightly less pain and popping in joints. Fatigue high. No appetite. Ice pick ear pain starting in morning happening several times.    PREDNISONE STARTED WEDNESDAY  Wed April 21: feeling about the same. Ringing in ears, neuropathy same, fatigue high. Appetite improved. Ice pick ear pain a couple times. Neuropathy seemed to improve towards the end of the day, when it usually is worsening. Felt nauseas and sick to stomach before bed with digestive issues. Dizzy spells all evening with static feeling. Ears ringing constant.  Thursday: neuropathy improved, still present and noticeable but I was able to walk normally and had more feeling than previous. Joints still cracking and popping. Not as nauseas or sick feeling throughout the day. No ear pain. Dizziness occasional, less than day before. Ears ringing constant.  Friday: neuropathy still improved but present and noticeable, able to walk more normally than previous. Joins still the same. Not as nauseas or sick feeling. Chest pains in sternum and stabbing ice pick ear pains on and off all day. Very painful in the ear. Light headed/easily motionsick, but better than Wednesday worse than thursday. Ears ringing constant.  Saturday: Neuropathy still improved, joints are stiff but not in pain. Light headed easily, ears ringing constant. This is the worst day for the ice pick ear pain yet. Repetitive ?attacks? concentrated in the morning enough to make me have to drop and hold my head. It was very painful and higher frequency than ever seen previously.   Sunday: Feeling sore in my hip joints. Ears ringing constantly. Ice pick ear pain only happened twice. Neuropathy slightly more than day previous but okay and balance still improved. Chest pains in sternum present. Episodes of blurred vision/double vision towards the end of the day.

Approximately 3-5 minutes post-vaccination, patient was seated, texting a message on cell phone, and fainted. Slumped out of chair face down. Witnessed by several volunteer employees. Not witnessed by pharmacist who had administered the vaccine. Volunteers called for help. Immediately pharmacist responded to patient. Loss of conscious noted. Patient was assessed and gently rolled to back with head support and began to regain consciousness, stiffened arms and legs noted. Patient asked, "Do you have a history of seizure disorder?" Initially unable to respond. Pharmacist requested 911 be called as is looked like a seizure. Asked again, and then patient shook head no and then verbal no. Muscles more relaxed. Stroke assessment performed with arms and legs equal to weight, no facial droop, verbal back to normal. Patient asked if he would like to sit up in chair after about 5 minutes on back. Patient complained of headache but no other injuries. Stated he had no bump on his head. Paramedics arrive in less than 10 minutes from call.  Assessed patient. Vitals normal. Skin color normal from pale. Paramedics assumed vasovagal fainting episode. Pharmacist agreed. Patient offered water and consumed 12 ounces. Stayed additional 30 minutes. Stood and sit tested for balance. Left without complaint.
CUR_ILL: Unknown, no history of seizure disorder
HISTORY: History of light-headedness when exposed to blood or needles.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: LEFT LOWER EXTREMITY ISCHEMIC LIMB; ARTERIAL THROMBOSIS A week after the first dose, patient develop acute onset of left 3rd toe tip pain and tenderness.This gradually progressed to pain under his metatarsal head in the left foot.  Gradually over the last 2 weeks, he has also noted increasing hip and buttock muscle fatigue with walking.  Two nights ago, he developed increasing pain in his left forefoot.  Yesterday, his left foot became numb and he went to Medical Center for evaluation.  While there, he was found to have an ischemic left leg with lack of Doppler signals in his left foot and subsequently underwent CT angiography.  This CT scan demonstrated left internal iliac occlusion, partially occlusive thrombus within the left external iliac artery with widely patent femoral popliteal system bilaterally.  However, his left peroneal and anterior tibial arteries were occluded for segments, while the distal left posterior tibial artery appears occluded, although this may represent contrast bolus timing issues He has no known prior history of thrombotic issues.  He has no family history of clotting abnormalities.  He denies any palpitations or history of cardiac arrhythmia.  He has been in sinus rhythm since his initial presentation.
LAB_DATA: 4/28/2021 PERCUTANEOUS, OPEN THROMBECTOMIES OF MULTIPLE LEFT LEG VESSEL Left leg arteriogram Left Iliac thrombectomy Percutaneous left popliteal, AT, peroneal and PT Open thrombectomy of left popliteal,AT, peroneal and PT Patch repair of tibial peroneal trunk with bovine pericardium  Findings: left Iliac thrombus and extensive and recurrent thrombosis of  all left tibial arteries  Other diagnostics:  Transthoracic Echocardiogram Arterial doppler duplex  studies of both lower extremities CT left lower extremities

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient admitted with left sided weakness on 4/21/21. First covid-19 vaccine (Moderna) received on 3/23/21. MRI/MRA shows acute infarcts of the right caudate body and striatum. H/o HTN, hep C with cirrhosis, COPD, tobacco abuse, alcohol use disorder, GTC seizure disorder. ECHO on 4/21/21 which was normal. Patient thought to be actively overusing alcohol at home. Patient was treated for stroke and discharged on medications to help with alcohol withdrawal symptoms (clonidine, gabapentin) as well as aspirin, plavix, and atorvastatin for new stroke. Thrombocytopenia noted (platelets 50K), however patient?s platelets have historically been low likely related to alcohol use. Per hospitalist discharge summary, low suspicion for vaccine induced thrombocytopenia. HIT Ab test ordered on 4/21/21, resulted negative. It seems to be coincidental that stroke occurred about a month after patient?s first covid-19 vaccine but reported to VAERS for completeness. Did not add covid-19 vaccine to patient?s allergy list. Patient received second covid-19 vaccine (Moderna) on 4/28/21.
LAB_DATA: 4/21/21 MRI/MRA Impression: 1. Head MRI: Acute infarcts of the right caudate body and striatum, with matched FLAIR hyperintensities. These are likely at least 6 hours-to-several days old. Negative for acute intracranial hemorrhage or significant mass effect. Two focal areas of old appearing microhemorrhages are noted in the right parietal lobe, potentially posttraumatic or amyloid related.  2. Head MRA-MRV:  A. No large vessel occlusion, aneurysm, dissection, or critical stenosis.  B. Enhancing oblong 20 mm structure within the left posterior orbit with layering fluid, incompletely assessed on this examination, but with imaging features suggestive of varix with stagnant flow or slow flow venous malformation. If indicated, consider nonemergent dedicated MRI orbits with Valsalva and time resolved angiography, when patient's clinical condition permits.  Labs 4/21/21 platelets 50K (historical platelets: 2/24/21 86K, 9/6/19 37K, 5/2/19 98K) 4/21/21 HIT Ab negative

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Approximately 4 weeks after first dose of Moderna vaccine, patient began to experience constant whooshing sound in left ear that wakes her from sleep and is extremely distracting and disruptive to daily life activities.  The symptoms are consistent with tinnitus. The patient went to see an ENT specialist who she sees for ongoing care. She had visited the provider in 2020 and had  her hearing screened. Her hearing was normal at the time in both ears. The patient visited her ENT in early April 2021 for the ear symptoms. The provider found no causes of the symptoms during her examination (ie: ear wax, issues with ear drums, etc) in either ear and scheduled a follow up MRI to assess whether the patient may have a brain tumor. Additionally, the provider conducted a hearing test and discovered that the patient's hearing acuity in her left ear is 10% below normal. So it has degraded since the visit in 2020.  The patient has additional specialist follow up scheduled with a otolaryngologist to assess alternate causes of the symptoms, which have not abated and which are extremely distressing to the patient. The constant sound in the patient's left ear has continued for approximately 10 weeks at this point, and she frequently experiences a feeling of distracting pressure in her left ear as well.
LAB_DATA: Hearing test conducted in early April 2021 - result was that patient has lost 10% of her hearing in her left ear. Brain MRI is scheduled for early May.

EMT visually assessed the patient's ear and saw no swelling, only light redness. Patient was advised to sit in the zero gravity chair for further evaluation. At 1227, baseline vital signs were taken, while patient was sitting: blood pressure: 114/68, heart rate: 77, respiratory rate: 12. Skin was cool, dry, and normal for ethnicity. Nurse then responded to EMT with patient. EMT asked the patient if she was taking any medications. She stated that she is taking WELLBUTRIN and has allergies to gluten and latex. At 1233, a second set of vitals were taken: blood pressure: 118/78, heart rate: 84, respiratory rate: 12. Skin was cool, dry, and normal for ethnicity. Patient was negative for orthostatic pressures. EMT advised the patient to continue to sit in the zero gravity chair for an additional 30 minutes, to observe for additional signs and symptoms. Patient was educated by EMT regarding the signs and symptoms to look out for and when the patient should contact her primary care provider. The patient was also given the information to sign up for V- safe as well as educated regarding the importance of doing so. After the observation time was completed, around 1: 00PM, the patient walked out of the site unassisted and with a steady gait.

I was too sore to get out of bed (body aches, headache) and was extremely light headed when I tried to sit up, so I had no choice but to call off my scheduled work shift for the day. Throughout the morning, my fever continued to increase despite taking Tylenol regularly (2-3 tablets every 4 hours), up to 101.8ï¿½F. I was too nauseous to eat, or really to even drink much, despite several spells of feverish sweating followed by chills/uncontrollable shivering. I stayed in bed nearly all day miserable and all but completely incapacitated. SYMPTOM_TEXT: The shot was administered very high on my right arm, slightly dorsal. About 6 hours after the shot, my arm started to get very sore and became hard to use.  By 11 hours afterward, the pain and weakness of my arm/shoulder became extremely uncomfortable and I began alternating taking Tylenol (1000mg) and Ibuprophen (600mg) every three hours (6 hours between the same drug), around the clock.  The following 2-4 days, my shoulder felt dislocated--it was very painful to move in some ways, felt weak, and I had some tingling/numbness in some of my fingers (most noticeably my middle finger).  Sleeping was difficult due to the pain. I purchased a sling and continued to rest, ice, and manage the pain. Each day there was some improvement.  On day 3 I saw a doctor about it.  She was not overly concerned about long-term affects, but suggested adding heat to my therapy.   I am now on day 7 after the shot, and although I do not have full range/use of my arm and some pain and weakness persists, it is much better.  I hope in another couple of days, it will be good as new.  Apart from the bad reaction in my arm, on day 2, I experienced some aches, fatigue, and slight chills.

PT stated she had not eaten anything all day and was given some snacks to eat while she was being observed.  After about 45 minutes pt was stood up and checked to see if she was still feeling light headed and felt normal and was released to her mother to go home. Pt was advised to drink plenty of water and take the rest of the day to relax and recover, and to call 911 if any other serious issues occurred.

I did not report it to the clinic staff.  In researching this allergic reaction is likely related to Polyethylene Glycol allergy.  When I got a colonoscopy a few years ago I used colo prep.  Back then my heart was pounding hard the night before and the day of the examination.  I did not know it was a side-effect from the solution.  Doctors could not explain why my heart rate was high but went ahead with the exam. With the current event it appears is the common link between then and the COVID vaccine.

4/2 - Had a physical where doctor mentioned some small bumps on my upper back. I'd never noticed this visually, nor had they itched or ever been otherwise noticeable/bothersome.  This first week was 'hypersensitive' to things I typically wouldn't be. 4/5 - Received my first vaccine. Slight/mild arm tenderness at injection site (left arm) on and off starting a few hrs later.  4/6 - Continued mild arm tenderness. Upper back (where previously noted bumps were) was very hot. Upper lip was minorly swollen (not visibly, by touch only)  4/7 -  Was very sensitive to some smells - flowers in my house were very intense which also resulted in minor headache. I don't typically have this type of reaction and the same flowers the days prior and after didn't elicit this response. Went to chiro for an adjustment that evening.  4/8 - Upper back and neck stiffness. Occasionally after an adjustment I'll be tight but never like this.  At some point this first week or possibly the week after, there were electric like 'pops' throughout my left side lower leg.  4/11 - Started Vitamin and Supplement regiment from doctor  4/12 - Started detox diet to remove all 'sensitive' foods. Had acupuncture.  4/13 or 14 - The injection site started minor itching and looked like a small bug bite (raised and rounded). Can't recall if this lasted 1 or 2 days.  At some point during the 2nd week and continuing through the 3rd week my sinus started acting up - this is not unusual and I don't attribute to the vaccine, but I do think that the vaccine contributed to the sinus issue making me feel more drained of energy and 'hot' all over (but not a full out fever) than 'normal' for when it (my left sinus) acts up.  4/19 - Upper back was hot and quite itchy (very small eczema like bumps) during the afternoon; in the evening arm also was itchy.  4/20 - Work up with rash on injection (left) arm - small area where injection was and larger area slightly below that. Rash was more hot, as opposed to itchy. Mild brain fog / lack of energy (though also didn't get a ton of sleep and my sinus was acting up too - don't think the sinus was likely related to the shot). Felt all over hot, but short of feverish.  4/22 - By end of day the rash was gone. Heart palpitations and could feel my heart beating against my chest all day long. Leg "throbbing pulse" in lower left leg - comes and goes.  At some point around here it became harder to breathe in the sense that I was breathing fine, but felt like I wasn't getting enough oxygen, i.e. needing to breathe deeper than normal and was getting tension in my temples.  4/23 - Minor heart "flutters" in the am and evening, but not during the day/as intense as the day before.  4/24 & 4/25 - leg "pulses" less noticeable, but still occurring. Alternating around the lower leg and upper leg - a few even up in buttocks area.  4/26 - leg "pulses" more noticeable - at times more of a sustained throb rather than quicker 'pulse'. Mostly in the lower leg and the upper leg right above the knee toward the interior of the thigh. Acupuncture in the evening specifically addressing my 'fire points' which were 'acting up' - felt overall more relaxed, leg pulses less noticeable and could more easily breathe.   4/27 to 4/29- leg 'pulses' still continue but 90-95% better than previously - not as frequent or severe.  Starting to occur some in the right leg now.  Began taking Xiao Chai Hu Tang herbs from acupuncturist to get ahead of potential side-effects from the 2nd vaccine.
LAB_DATA: No tests, but did see a PCP on 4/27 to discuss symptoms and whether or not second vaccine should be taken.
OTHER_MEDS: 1 week post vaccine started taking:  N-acetyl0l-cysteine, magnesium taurate, L-glutamine, phosphatidylcholine, and shake supplements (InflammaCore, Better Breakfast) to address digestive concerns / food sensitivity reactions.
HISTORY: sinus issues which come and go; a fore mentioned food sensitivities/digestion/'leaky gut' issues over the past few years.

ALLERGIES: No allergies, but sensitivity to:  gluten, yogurt, eggs, soy, nuts, etc

Medical history includes history of anxiety and bipolar disorder, currently takes medication lamictal. Interventions done for client  include laying down in gravity chair and vital signs were taken at 12:03 PM: BP 158/96; pulse 78, respirations 18. Orthostatic vital signs were taken at 12:08 PM BP 162/100; pulse 78. Client was alert and oriented x4 during whole interaction with Medic . Client refused 911 call. At 12:16 PM client  verbalized symptoms resolved and nurse  recommended for stable vitals before being able to leave facility. Final vital signs were taken at 12:25 PM: BP 148/82; pulse 76; oxygen saturation of 99%. Client  left facility walking safely with steady gait at 12:30 PM.

Client received his vaccine and during his 15-minute monitoring period, he passed out. They took his glucose which was 87.  His vitals were stable by the time they made the decision to leave. They told him to continue sitting and monitoring for 15 minutes and have someone assist him in walking around some. Once he felt good to leave, he would be allowed to go home.
