To Whom It May Concern:  Dear Sir/Ma?am:  Good day. I am emailing to report a possible adverse event/s for the COVID-19 Vaccine(Moderna), that I had last February 18, 2021, at 8:45 am. I was fine the entire day of Thursday, February 18, 2021, until Friday afternoon, but on Friday evening of March 19, I had chest pain, palpitations(reached 130), my lips, legs, and arms trembled, and my b/p reached 188/89. Because of muscle pain localized in the chest, and as I just had the vaccination less than 48 hours earlier, I was compelled to rush to the ER to make sure it was not a heart attack. During the ER Consult, my Potassium Level was low. I feel that we have to look into the causality if the vaccine could also cause hypokalemia. Additionally, I had the same symptoms last Saturday evening(February 20) evening around 8pm. I had to call a friend to stay with me as my b/p reached 193/93. It subsided around midnight:116/72. I sent an email last February 22, 2021, but I did not receive a reply.

Patient was a client at a drive-through COVID-19 clinic. Patients Father was driving and the patient was seated in the front passenger seat. After receiving vaccine, FOC drove forward and parked in an observation lot that was staffed by 3 RNs. FOC reported to an observation lot attendant that patient, Patient was losing vision (narrowing), shaking, and then stopped responding. The observation lot attendant noted loss of consciousness, reclined patient in the seat and elevated feet above the heart by placing them on the car dashboard.  At 1535, 911 was notified by RN. When car door was opened by the attending observation lot worker, client began regaining consciousness. Client was given apple juice and crackers and vitals were taken. At 1540, Patient blood pressure measured 91/60, pulse oximeter reading of 96% saturation, and heart rate 72bpm. Paramedics arrived to the scene at 1545 and assessed the client; patient was not transported. Father was instructed by paramedics of warning signs and when to seek further care. FOC and patient were advised to inform PCP and to report this instance when receiving future vaccines. FOC and patient remained onsite for 15 minutes following Paramedic care and were dismissed when patient and FOC reported that they felt comfortable leaving.

The requirement of this vaccine is that you sit and wait to be watched for 15-30 minutes after receiving your dose. Post-jab (within 5 minutes), I felt a tingling and numbness in my arm. This was followed quickly by a palpating heartbeat and rush of intense dizziness. I informed the folks who were in the watch room that I felt I was having a negative reaction, and they immediately tended to me, putting an O2 sensor and BP cuff on. For the next 40 minutes, I experienced waves of dizziness and my heart was racing. My BP jumped around a bit, but never into dangerous areas. Breathing was never compromised. Staff required I lay down on a mat. I requested a Benadryl, having had a previous anaphylactic episode from an allergy shot when I was 13 and concerned this could be the onset of that. After about 30 minutes and benadryl the racing heart subsided, but I continued to have waves of dizziness overcome me. After about 40 minutes of laying down and heart rate no longer racing, I decided to try to walk to car to go home and rest. I was unable to walk, overcome again with dizziness and with legs that felt weighted, or rubbery. After another 10 minutes or so of sitting and waiting for waves of dizziness to stop, I decided to allow a nurse to wheel me upstairs to Urgent Care.   Urgent Care doc concluded that I was not experiencing life threatening symptoms and was likely being told by my body that I needed to rest. I agreed with this assessment. By the time I left Urgent Care, I had been experiencing waves of dizziness for 2 hours, and the heart racing that had accompanied it had stopped after I took Benadryl. I felt comfortable following her instructions to go home and rest.   I slept for several hours after returning home and had an uneventful night. I woke up this morning  (4/29) with blurry vision in my left eye, followed by a large headache. The blurred vision has dissipated, but I continue to have a headache, low-grade fever (between 99-100) and an overall sick feeling.
OTHER_MEDS: Tylenol, Docusate, Cyclobenzaprine, Cephalexin. Stopped Oxycodone 4/27/21 (prescribed 30 3miligram tablets for 4/23-4/27)

23-year-old-male presented for a Moderna COVID-19 vaccine. The patient was seated with his feet planted firmly on the floor. Immediately following vaccination, the patient had some blood running down his arm. I reached for a cotton swab to apply pressure and stop the bleeding, but the patient began to faint. I immediately positioned myself next to the patient; and held his head and arm to keep him in a sitting position. The patient regained consciousness after about twenty seconds. I began talking with the patient to ensure it was only a fainting spell. The patient was groggy but became clear-headed after about a minute. Upon further discussion, the patient stated this happens every time he sees blood, has bloodwork done or receives vaccines. The patient recounted a time when he cut his hand at work and fainted immediately. The patient was doing deep breathing exercises immediately after regaining consciousness. When asked, he said it helps him focus. I asked the patient if he wanted us to call anyone to pick him up but he refused. The patient was advised to remain seated, and we would transition him to the waiting area once he felt stable enough. After about 5 minutes the patient was helped to the waiting area (from our counseling room about 10-15 feet away). I advised him to remain in the waiting area for 30 minutes for further monitoring. The patient was offered juice, water and a snack but declined. After the 30 minute waiting period, the patient was clear-headed and appeared to be in the same state as when he arrived for the vaccine.
Patient reported double vision and dizziness after his vaccination. Advised patient to call his PCP

Patient with no known prior history of coronary artery disease,  woke up early morning between 4 and 5 with severe substernal chest discomfort, associated with some dyspnea. He had the 2nd COVID Moderna shot 2 days prior and has been experiencing mild fever, and chills. He did not get relief with ASA and antacid, and elected to come in . ECG at presentation showed left bundle branch block which was not present on previous ECG done in the hospital and stress test 2 years ago. His initial high sensitivity troponin was markedly elevated around 2500 ng/ml, and second set withint next 60 minutes rose to over 4000 ng/ml, consistent with acute coronary syndrome. Urgent coronary angiography was performed which did not reveal any culprit lesion. A stat echocardiogram showed normal EF and valve function. He was observed for 24 hours and discharged without incident on medical therapy.

She raised a red card then left to speak with someone about what to do.  They thought it would be ok and that I just need to sit in the lobby for 15 min.  After waiting in the lobby for  the 15 mins after the shot with no problems, my husband drove us home.  About 10 mins into the drive home the left side of my face, under my chin, and the top of my left hand felt numb.  That feeling lasted for at least 24 hours.  Then I just seemed more tired than usual. However, somewhere a few days after the shot, I began to feel a systemic prickly sensation.  I sort of expected a rash or something might be manifesting, but nothing.  Had the feeling for about two weeks. Starting this past Sunday, April 25 I noticed the left side numbness back again on my face and arm.  I just ignored it all and figured that was normal as the medicine was working.  Then, my 31 year old called that following Tuesday and said she was having numbness and tingling that started around week three after her first COVID dose.  She saw a doctor before her second dose and wanted to see if it was safe for her to have the next shot.  Doc determined paresthesia and thought ok for the next dose.  She did get the last dose and the tingling in her face, mouth, and extremities is continuing  to this day.  She saw her doc this morning and is on a list to see a neuro team in a few weeks with the hope the symptoms will resolve before then. Given my talk with her, I decided to take my symptoms seriously and called the vaccination line and they suggested I consult with my doc.  After today, I have cancelled my second dose set for May 1 in order to see how my daughter's COVID issue resolves.  Then, will see if my symptoms resolve before considering my second COVID shot.  Doc said to monitor symptoms and will follow up more if things progress.
OTHER_MEDS: Only one table of D3, 1000IUs,  maybe 4 days a week.
PRIOR_VAX: Flu shot 20 or so years ago; left side numbness; don't know type
ALLERGIES: Flu vaccine reaction about 20 years ago.  About 20 minutes after the shot, the left side of my face and arm went numb.  I called the clinic after I got home, they said to keep an eye for any worsening, and it resolved within 24 hours.

Reports 2 days of left-sided chest pain w/ periumbilical abd pain and enlarging abdomen. Pt believes these are 2/2 covid vaccination. Chest pain is described as constant generalized discomfort under left breast that worsens with pressure. Also worse with deep inspiration. No radiation or migration since onset. Pt describes abdominal pain as periumbilical tightness, "pain". Describes subjective, unmeasured fevers that "come and go" over last week.    When asked to repeat the story of what happened on arrival to the unit, wife speaks for the patient since he is slightly dyspnic. States this morning, went to small clinic, husband had a headache and slight fever. Clinic said to come in to the big hospital. Fever and pain in legs and head, started a few days after he got the covid vaccine. The fever came and went. Didn't measure the fever.  Also has some problems with Abdominal pain - doesn't know how to describe it. Feels like stomach ache. Stomach pain is getting better. Has since gone away since arriving to the hospital.  He denies any cough, denies chills, denies nausea or vomiting.   States he took some medications at home for constipation because he felt like he couldn't go. From the conversation it appears he does not take lactulose for HE, more for constipation.    ED workup included an Xray, CT C/A/P with multifocal lung lesions suspicious for multifocal pneumonia. Lactate of 16. Na of 124. Noted to be anemic and thrombocytopenic. UA cloudy, pyuric, w/protien >100.   Chest and abdominal pain resolved by the time pt was examined on the floor. Still tachypnic and tachycardic. Stated most bothersome was feeling anxious. Has anxiety at a baseline. Not complaining of any pain at the moment. Cannot describe chest pain in more detail, put his hand over the right side of his chest and presses on it but does not say if it hurt more when he would press on it, does not say it was reproducible. Not painful when he touches or presses on it now.    Per chart, patient recently re-established care after long-time from follow up during pandemic. I am the Infectious Diseases attending asked to see him for septic shock. He developed septic shock and respiratory failure requiring mechanical ventilation and 3 vasopressors. Pulmonary embolism; died - autopsy showed multiple blood clots all over his body - pelvic area, hearts,arteries, lungs; This spontaneous case was reported by a consumer and describes the occurrence of THROMBOSIS (died - autopsy showed multiple blood clots all over his body - pelvic area, hearts,arteries, lungs) and PULMONARY EMBOLISM (Pulmonary embolism) in an 83-year-old male patient who received mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (batch nos. 039A21A and 003A21A) for COVID-19 vaccination.     Concurrent medical conditions included Diabetes, Prostate cancer and Memory loss. Concomitant products included METFORMIN for Diabetes.   On 05-Mar-2021, the patient received first dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) 1 dosage form. On 02-Apr-2021, received second dose of mRNA-1273 (Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine) (Intramuscular) dosage was changed to 1 dosage form. On 04-Apr-2021, the patient experienced THROMBOSIS (died - autopsy showed multiple blood clots all over his body - pelvic area, hearts,arteries, lungs) (seriousness criterion death). On an unknown date, the patient experienced PULMONARY EMBOLISM (Pulmonary embolism) (seriousness criterion death). The patient died on 04-Apr-2021. The reported cause of death was Pulmonary embolism. An autopsy was performed. The autopsy-determined cause of death was multiple blood clots.            Action taken with mRNA-1273 in response to the event was not applicable  Other concomitant medications were reported included unspecified medications for memory loss and diabetes.  No treatment information was provided.; Sender's Comments: This is an 83-year-old, male patient who received mRNA-1273 Vaccine who experienced multiple thrombosis and died, 2 days after receiving second dose of vaccine.  Medical history includes Diabetes, and Prostate cancer.  Conmeds including some unspecified medications for memory loss and diabetes. The autopsy-determined cause of death was multiple blood clots.  Very limited information has been reported at this time. Further information is expected,; Reported Cause(s) of Death: Pulmonary embolism; Autopsy-determined Cause(s) of Death: multiple blood clots

Patient was in the post-vaccination area seated after her shot.  About 10 minutes after receiving the vaccine, she stated that she started feeling lightheaded.  She fainted and fell out of her chair.  I  immediately went to her and found her conscious, but very disoriented.  She stated that she felt nauseated.  911 had been called;  I stayed with her until they arrived.  They fitted her with a cervical counter and raised her to  a seated position and took her vitals.  She was able to stand and get on the stretcher with their assistance.  The EMTs stayed with her and monitored her  vitals until her mother arrived to take her home.  I spoke with her by phone at 6PM.   She stated that she felt fine  now (except for a bump on her head).  She stated that she was afraid of needles and that anxiety probably caused the incident.

Approximately 5-6 days after my second Pfizer vaccine dose, I began having paresthesias in patchy areas on the outside of my right ankle. Over the next 3-4 weeks, the paresthesias (burning,  tingling, temperature sensation) progressed to the other leg and then ascended up the legs bilaterally to the upper thigh area. I consulted my neurologist and he ordered a MRI of the cervical and thoracic spine. The day after the MRI (4/15/21), I had two seizures in the morning after being seizure free for a year. I had significant fatigue and felt very poorly. A few hours later, I had a sudden onset of severe bilateral leg weakness. Because I could not walk, EMS was called. I went to Hospital where I was admitted for leg weakness. Additional imaging was performed. I was able to walk a few steps after receiving a dose of 1g solumedrol via IV that night. My symptoms improved over the next few days with IV steroid treatment. I was discharged on 4/19/21 and was advised to follow up with outpatient neurology. My neurologist initially diagnosed acute transverse myelitis and ordered physical therapy. I continued a steroid taper for 6 days after hospital discharge. Today (4/29/21), my symptoms have improved but continue to have adverse effects. I am able to walk but tire quickly and am very fatigued. I have been unable to work since hospital discharge.
LAB_DATA: MRI - brain, cervical, thoracic and lumbar spine - degenerative disc changes and herniations in cervical and lumbar spine, brain - chiari malformation 1, thoracic - syrinx at T6-7. I consulted a neurosurgeon about the chiari malformation and syrinx and he advised that they were misdiagnosed. He identified the vaccine as the cause of the symptoms. Lyme, B12, Vit D, Sed Rate, CMP,CBC normal in hospital. Slight elevation in CRP EEG done in hospital - normal No lumbar puncture done
OTHER_MEDS: Lamotrigine, levothyroxine, sertraline, vitamin D, multivitamin
HISTORY: Partial seizure disorder - well controlled on lamotrigine hypothyroidism mild exercise induced asthma

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Approximately 8 hours after receiving the vaccine  I started to feel ill . My symptoms were chills that felt like continuous seizure activity,  fever highest temp was 103.6 , severe muscle aches which I could barely walk needing assistance, nausea ,dizziness , difficulty breathing with congestion and lightheadedness. At three AM I woke up with the room spinning, I couldn't focus, felt like I was falling. I had horrible pain in my back. I was sweating and vomiting.  My husband carried me to the car and brought me to the ER. At the Er I was given a patch for my back pain, medicine for the dizziness and nausea. The dizziness didn't subside. I couldn't walk. I told them I had gotten the vaccine two weeks before and they said it wasn't related. I was diagnosed with a bladder infection, high blood sugar, and vertigo. I was discharged in the evening but with no improvement.  I was not able to focus or walk for days. I saw my OBGYN, he was the only doctor I could see right away and he referred me to an ENT. The ENT can't see me until the end of June.  I wasn't able to drive for weeks. I am slowly regaining my balance but still feel waves of dizziness and my eyes can't focus well when I am reading. The back pain is gone. My OBGYN also doesn't feel the dizziness is related.

Patient is a 40 y.o. female who presents for evaluation of adverse reaction to Johnson and Johnson COVID vaccine (received on 4/11/21).  She received the vaccine on April 11th, around 2:30 p.m. at 8:00 p.m. that night she developed fever with temp 100.4ï¿½, chills, headache, nausea and body aches.  At 10:00 p.m. that night she developed palpitations, heart racing, shortness of breath, tightness in her throat and chest.  She was unable to sleep that night.  The next day on April 12th, she continued to have low-grade fever with temp 99ï¿½, shortness of breath, chest tightness.  She reports taking a pregnancy test at home which revealed a faint positive pink line.  That night she took Tylenol which helped relieve some of her symptoms.  On April 13th, she continued to have shortness of breath and chest tightness, her heart palpitations improved slightly.  She reports retaking the home pregnancy test and this time it was negative.  On April 14th, she had a same-day clinic visit, labs that day revealed slightly elevated D-dimer and normal chest x-ray.  She continued to have shortness of breath and on April 16th, she presented to the ER due to sudden onset of bad headache, nausea, diarrhea and heart palpitations.  She was discharged from the ER with close follow-up with her primary care doctor.  Her symptoms did not improve and subsequently on April 20th, she began to have left-sided facial numbness.  On April 21st, she went to the ER and was found to have left-sided facial weakness and suspected Bell's palsy.  She was admitted for further diagnostic workup (CT Brain normal, MRI Brain normal, and MRV Brain with no evidence of venous sinus thrombosis, carotid doppler normal, MRA Brain normal, MRI sella (pituitary) normal), and treatment was initiated with prednisone and antiviral medications.  On April 23rd she developed left arm weakness as well. She was discharged with closed follow up with her PMD and specialists. She recently was seen by pulm Dr and scheduled for PFTs. She is nearly completed with course of prednisone and valacyclovir, left facial weakness slightly improved but not resolved, has follow up with neuro this week.
LAB_DATA: CT Brain normal, MRI Brain normal, and MRV Brain with no evidence of venous sinus thrombosis, carotid doppler normal, MRA Brain normal, MRI sella (pituitary) normal)

I asked if she would like some liquid Benadryl and she said yes. I gave her 10 ml of liquid diphenhydramine 12.5mg/5ml. After about 1-2 minutes she said she felt better. I asked if she would like to repeat the dose of Benadryl and she said no she was feeling better. She was able to breathe and talk at this time. After her 15 minute time limit for observation expired I asked her to remain seated in observation. I again offered another dose of Benadryl and she said she did not feel like she needed it that she was feeling much better. I went to get her a cup of water and asked her to take small sips. She remained in observation for approximately 15 additional minutes. I asked the patient before she left if she wanted another dose of Benadryl but she said she felt good and had Zyrtec if she needed anything, but didn't think she needed any more medicine. When I woke up the day after (Day #2) being given the vaccine I was extremely tired exhausted, I had intense chills and hot flashes. Never a fever. I felt nauseated. Completely lethargic. Muscle aches all over my body, was hard to move. I couldn't stay awake. My eyes hurt. I had intense migraines.  And no appetite. My right arm hurt, but not as bad as many others' reported.  I took ibuprofen to help, it didn't. I drank lots of water and gatorade zero for the electrolytes. It didn't help either.  On day #3, this was when it got scary. The previous  symptoms carried over, minus the nausea and I was able to be mobile (less lethargic).  But something new started to happen. I took my dog out for a short walk, a slow pace, I am very athletic, and I had shortness of breath. I was winded from just walking slowly. Then the brain fog started to set in. This I hated the most. I wasn't able to comprehend things. I tried to assemble an item I bought from Amazon and it was extremely hard to follow simple instructions. I wasn't able to see clearly for some reason. And even comprehending emails that I was receiving was troublesome. I kept drinking water, and was able to eat a little. Had two more bottles of Gatorade Zero.  On day 3, most of all the symptoms subsided except that I still got winded from movement.  On day 4, I was fine.
LAB_DATA: I can't go to the doctor, that costs money. We are in a pandemic and I need to save money to pay for my mortgage and bills.
